{"title_page": "Isaac of Ourville", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Isaac of Corbeil|Isaac ben Dorbolo}}\n\n'''Isaac of [[Ourville-en-Caux|Ourville]]''' ({{lang-he|{{hebrew|\u05d9\u05e6\u05d7\u05e7 \u05de\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9\u05dc}}}} ''Yi\u1e63\u1e25aq me-Orvil'', {{floruit|late 13th century}}<ref name=\"Emanuel\" />) was a medieval French rabbi, author of the as yet unpublished ''Menahel'', a book of ''[[halakha]]'' (Jewish ritual law).\n\nIsaac appears to have been a contemporary of [[Perez of Corbeil]] (died {{circa|lk=no|1297}});<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Renan |first=Ernest |year=1877\n |chapter=Les rabbins fran\u00e7ais |chapterurl=//books.google.com/books?id=aGIOAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA448\n |editor-last=Haur\u00e9au |editor-first=B.\n |title=Histoire litt\u00e9raire de la France |volume=XXVII |page=448\n |publisher=[[Imprimerie nationale]] |location=Paris |lccn=f01002304}}</ref> \nIsaac cites [[Moses of Coucy]]'s ''Semag'', from the generation before Perez, while segments of Isaac's ''Menahel'' are, in turn, cited alongside the Perez's teachings.<ref name=\"Ez Hayyim\"/> \nHis master was Hayyim of [[Blois]],<ref name=\"Gallia Judaica\">{{Cite book\n |last=Gross |first=Heinrich |author-link=Heinrich Gross (rabbi) |year=1897\n |url=//books.google.com/books?id=ycsrAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA27\n |title=Gallia Judaica |language=French |location=Paris |publisher=L. Cerf |pages=27\u201328 |lccn=51050586}}</ref> \nwho is possibly identical with Hayyim ben Isaac the Frenchman ({{lang-he|{{hebrew|\u05d7\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05df \u05d9\u05e6\u05d7\u05e7 \u05d4\u05e6\u05e8\u05e4\u05ea\u05d9}}}}), the author of ''Ez Hayyim'' on Jewish monetary law, a disciple of [[Samuel of Evreux]].<ref name=\"Ez Hayyim\">{{cite book\n |last=Goldmints |first=A. Y. |year=2001\n |chapter=Foreword |title=Ez Hayyim\n |editor=<!--i.e. cataloged author:-->Hayyim ben Isaac\n |others=Goldmints, A. Y. (ed.) |lccn=2004418780 |language=Hebrew\n |publisher=Mekhon Yerushalayim |location=Jerusalem |page=12}}</ref>\n\n[[Eliakim Carmoly|Carmoly]] and others read {{hebrew|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9\u05dc}} as \"[[Orbeil]]\", a village in the [[Puy-de-D\u00f4me]] [[department (France)|department]], while [[Heinrich Gross|Gross]] considered this unlikely, as Orbeil probably had no Jewish population in medieval times. According to Gross, {{hebrew|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9\u05dc}} is probably Ourville ([[Ourville-en-Caux]]), [[Seine-Maritime]], or perhaps [[Orville, Orne|Orville]], [[Orne]].<ref name=\"Gallia Judaica\" /> \nIsaac is thus sometimes named {{hebrew|\u05d4\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05dc\u05d9}} '''''HaOrvili''''' (or '''''HaOrbeli'''''). \nHe was confused by [[Samuel David Luzzato]] with a similarly named rabbinical authority, [[Isaac ben Dorbolo]], after [[Solomon Judah Loeb Rapoport|Rapoport]]'s misinterpretation of the latter's [[patronymic]] as \"[[wikt:d'|d']]Orbolo\".<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Taylor |first=Charles |year=1900 |author-link=Charles Taylor (Hebraist)\n |title=Appendix to Sayings of the Jewish Fathers\n |publisher=University Press |url=https://archive.org/details/anappendixtosay00taylgoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/anappendixtosay00taylgoog/page/n25 13]}}</ref>\n\nSelections of his halakhic book, ''HaMenahel'' ({{lang-he|{{hebrew|\u05d4\u05de\u05e0\u05d4\u05dc}}}} \"the Guide\"), were incorporated in the closely related pair of halakhic works, ''Orhot Hayyim'' by [[Aaron ben Jacob ha-Kohen]] and ''[[Kol Bo]]'',<ref name=\"Gallia Judaica\" /> and, anonymously, in the halakhic decisions of [[Menahem Recanati]].<ref name=\"Emanuel\">{{cite journal\n |last=Emanuel |first=Simha |year=2008\n |script-title=he:\u05e4\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9 \u05e8' \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05dd \u05de\u05e8\u05e7\u05e0\u05d8\u05d9\n |journal=Shenaton ha-mishpa\u1e6d ha-\u02bbIvri\n |volume=25\n |pages=158\u2013159\n |lccn=74647727 |publisher=[[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]}}</ref> \nOnce considered lost, parts of the ''Menahel'' are now known to exist in manuscript.<ref name=\"Emanuel\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:13th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:13th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n\n\n{{France-rabbi-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Isaac of Corbeil|Isaac ben Dorbolo}}\n\n'''Isaac of [[Ourville-en-Caux|Ourville]]''' ({{lang-he|{{hebrew|\u05d9\u05e6\u05d7\u05e7 \u05de\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9\u05dc}}}} ''Yi\u1e63\u1e25aq me-Orvil'', {{floruit|late 13th century}}<ref name=\"Emanuel\" />) was a medieval French rabbi, author of the as yet unpublished ''Menahel'', a book of ''[[halakha]]'' (Jewish ritual law).\n\nIsaac appears to have been a contemporary of [[Perez of Corbeil]] (died {{circa|lk=no|1297}});<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Renan |first=Ernest |year=1877\n |chapter=Les rabbins fran\u00e7ais |chapterurl=//books.google.com/books?id=aGIOAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA448\n |editor-last=Haur\u00e9au |editor-first=B.\n |title=Histoire litt\u00e9raire de la France |volume=XXVII |page=448\n |publisher=[[Imprimerie nationale]] |location=Paris |lccn=f01002304}}</ref> \nIsaac cites [[Moses of Coucy]]'s ''Semag'', from the generation before Perez, while segments of Isaac's ''Menahel'' are, in turn, cited alongside the Perez's teachings.<ref name=\"Ez Hayyim\"/> \nHis master was Hayyim of [[Blois]],<ref name=\"Gallia Judaica\">{{Cite book\n |last=Gross |first=Heinrich |author-link=Heinrich Gross (rabbi) |year=1897\n |url=//books.google.com/books?id=ycsrAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA27\n |title=Gallia Judaica |language=French |location=Paris |publisher=L. Cerf |pages=27\u201328 |lccn=51050586}}</ref> \nwho is possibly identical with Hayyim ben Isaac the Frenchman ({{lang-he|{{hebrew|\u05d7\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05df \u05d9\u05e6\u05d7\u05e7 \u05d4\u05e6\u05e8\u05e4\u05ea\u05d9}}}}), the author of ''Ez Hayyim'' on Jewish monetary law, a disciple of [[Samuel of Evreux]].<ref name=\"Ez Hayyim\">{{cite book\n |last=Goldmints |first=A. Y. |year=2001\n |chapter=Foreword |title=Ez Hayyim\n |editor=<!--i.e. cataloged author:-->Hayyim ben Isaac\n |others=Goldmints, A. Y. (ed.) |lccn=2004418780 |language=Hebrew\n |publisher=Mekhon Yerushalayim |location=Jerusalem |page=12}}</ref>\n\n[[Eliakim Carmoly|Carmoly]] and others read {{hebrew|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9\u05dc}} as \"[[Orbeil]]\", a village in the [[Puy-de-D\u00f4me]] [[department (France)|department]], while [[Heinrich Gross|Gross]] considered this unlikely, as Orbeil probably had no Jewish population in medieval times. According to Gross, {{hebrew|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9\u05dc}} is probably Ourville ([[Ourville-en-Caux]]), [[Seine-Maritime]], or perhaps [[Orville, Orne|Orville]], [[Orne]].<ref name=\"Gallia Judaica\" /> \nIsaac is thus sometimes named {{hebrew|\u05d4\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05dc\u05d9}} '''''HaOrvili''''' (or '''''HaOrbeli'''''). \nHe was confused by [[Samuel David Luzzato]] with a similarly named rabbinical authority, [[Isaac ben Dorbolo]], after [[Solomon Judah Loeb Rapoport|Rapoport]]'s misinterpretation of the latter's [[patronymic]] as \"[[wikt:d'|d']]Orbolo\".<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Taylor |first=Charles |year=1900 |author-link=Charles Taylor (Hebraist)\n |title=Appendix to Sayings of the Jewish Fathers\n |publisher=University Press |url=https://archive.org/details/anappendixtosay00taylgoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/anappendixtosay00taylgoog/page/n25 13]}}</ref>\n\nSelections of his halakhic book, ''HaMenahel'' ({{lang-he|{{hebrew|\u05d4\u05de\u05e0\u05d4\u05dc}}}} \"the Guide\"), were incorporated in the closely related pair of halakhic works, ''Orhot Hayyim'' by [[Aaron ben Jacob ha-Kohen]] and ''[[Kol Bo]]'',<ref name=\"Gallia Judaica\" /> and, anonymously, in the halakhic decisions of [[Menahem Recanati]].<ref name=\"Emanuel\">{{cite journal\n |last=Emanuel |first=Simha |year=2008\n |script-title=he:\u05e4\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9 \u05e8' \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05dd \u05de\u05e8\u05e7\u05e0\u05d8\u05d9\n |journal=Shenaton ha-mishpa\u1e6d ha-\u02bbIvri\n |volume=25\n |pages=158\u2013159\n |lccn=74647727 |publisher=[[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]}}</ref> \nOnce considered lost, parts of the ''Menahel'' are now known to exist in manuscript.<ref name=\"Emanuel\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:13th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:13th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n\n\n{{France-rabbi-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_of_Ourville"}
{"title_page": "The Summons (hymn)", "text_new": "{{about|a hymn||Summons (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = The Summons\n| type                = \n| image               = <!-- without leading \"File:\" -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| translation         = <!-- to English, if hymn name is a different language -->\n| native_name         = <!-- if hymn name is the translation -->\n| native_name_lang    = <!-- two-letter code -->\n| composer            = [[John L. Bell]]\n| genre               = [[Hymn]]\n| occasion            = \n| text                =  \n| language            = \n| written             = 1987\n| based_on            = {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Mark|chapter=1|verse=16-20}} \n| meter               = 8.8.4.4.8.8 with refrain\n| melody              = \"Kelvingrove\"\n| composed            = <!-- {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}|end_date={{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}|location=}} -->\n| published           = \n| misc                =  \n}}\n\n\"'''The Summons'''\", also called \"'''Will You Come and Follow Me'''\",<ref name=hn>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/text/will_you_come_and_follow_me |title=The Summons |publisher=Hymnary.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref> is a Scottish Christian hymn. It was written by [[John L. Bell]] in 1987.\n\n== History ==\nBell composed \"The Summons\" after being accepted into the [[Iona Community]] in 1980.<ref name=gbod /> It was first included in the Iona Community's ''Heaven Shall Not Wait: Songs of Creation, the Incarnation, and the Life of Jesus'', published by their Wild Goose Resource Group in 1987. \"The Summons\" has been published in many hymn books beyond the Iona Community and the United Kingdom, including those by the [[United Church of Canada]] and the [[Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/instances?qu=in%3Ainstances%20textAuthNumber%3Awill_you_come_and_follow_me&sort=hymnalTitle |title=All Instances, The Summons |publisher=Hymnary.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/hymnal/GG2013?page=7 |title=Glory to God: the Presbyterian Hymnal|publisher=Hymnary.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-30}}</ref> It also appears in \u201cWonder, Love, and Praise,\u201d the addendum hymnal of the [[Episcopal Church (United States)]] and \"The Faith We Sing\", a supplemental hymnal of the [[United Methodist Church]].\n\n== Composition and usage ==\n\"The Summons\" is set to the tune of Kelvingrove, a traditional Scottish melody. Its text contains thirteen questions asked by Jesus in the [[grammatical person|first person]].<ref name=ion /><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.singingthefaithplus.org.uk/?p=847 |title=Where can we find you, Lord Jesus our Master?  |publisher=Methodist Church of Great Britain |date= |accessdate=2014-06-09}}</ref> The initial four stanzas with the questions are in Jesus' voice, and the fifth stanza is the singer's response to them.<ref name=hn /> The hymn is based on [[Mark 1]]:16\u201320 and alludes to Jesus calling his disciples to follow him.<ref name=ion>{{cite web|last=Vroege |first=David A. |url=http://www.reformedworship.org/article/december-2001/songs-iona |title=Songs from Iona |publisher=Reformed Worship |date= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref> C. Michael Hawn calls it a prophetic Christian hymn and mentioned that it contains words uncommon to other hymns.<ref name=gbod>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.gbod.org/lead-your-church/history-of-hymns/resource/history-of-hymns-the-summons |title=History of Hymns &#124; The Summons |publisher=GBOD |date= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref> It has been used as an example of how a Christian should react to fear and love<ref>{{cite book | first =Eva  | last =McIntyre | title =A Quiet Mind: Uniting Body, Mind and Emotions in Christian Spirituality | publisher = John Hunt Publishing | edition =  | year = 2011| isbn = 1780990057 | page = 26}}</ref> as well as being written as an example of covenantal discipleship.<ref>{{cite book | first =Kenneth  | last =Cuthbertson | title =The Last Presbyterian?: Remembering the Faith of My Forebears| publisher = Wipf and Stock Publishers | edition =  | year = 2013| isbn = 1620328704 | page = 95}}</ref> The hymn is used as a vocational and youth hymn because the words are easier to learn for younger people compared with other hymns.<ref>{{cite book | first =Tim  | last =Sledge | title =Get a Life!: Life Goals for Young People| publisher = Church House Publishing | edition =  | year = 2008| isbn = 1620328704 | page = 46}}</ref> In 2014, the hymn was used at [[Blackburn Cathedral]] at a service performed by the [[Bishop of Blackburn]] to commemorate 20 years since the first [[ordination of women in the Church of England]] as well as the [[Diocese of Blackburn]]'s decision to support the ordination of women as [[bishop]]s in the [[Church of England]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.lep.co.uk/news/special-service-to-mark-20-years-of-women-s-ministry-1-6629019 |title=Special service to mark 20 years of women\u2019s ministry  |work=Lancashire Evening Post |date= |accessdate=2014-06-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.spiritandsong.com/compositions/30338 Lyrics at ''Spirit and Song'']\n* [https://youtube.com/watch?v=TkuowlcfcOw Recording on YouTube by user DO(re)MI]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Summons, The}}\n[[Category:Scottish Christian hymns]]\n[[Category:Scottish music]]\n[[Category:1987 songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|a hymn||Summons (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = The Summons\n| type                = \n| image               = <!-- without leading \"File:\" -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| translation         = <!-- to English, if hymn name is a different language -->\n| native_name         = <!-- if hymn name is the translation -->\n| native_name_lang    = <!-- two-letter code -->\n| composer            = [[John L. Bell]]\n| genre               = [[Hymn]]\n| occasion            = \n| text                =  \n| language            = \n| written             = 1987\n| based_on            = {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Mark|chapter=1|verse=16-20}} \n| meter               = 8.8.4.4.8.8 with refrain\n| melody              = \"Kelvingrove\"\n| composed            = <!-- {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}|end_date={{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}|location=}} -->\n| published           = \n| misc                =  \n}}\n\n\"'''The Summons'''\", also called \"'''Will You Come and Follow Me'''\",<ref name=hn>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/text/will_you_come_and_follow_me |title=The Summons |publisher=Hymnary.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref> is a Scottish Christian hymn. It was written by [[John L. Bell]] in 1987.\n\n== History ==\nBell composed \"The Summons\" after being accepted into the [[Iona Community]] in 1980.<ref name=gbod /> It was first included in the Iona Community's ''Heaven Shall Not Wait: Songs of Creation, the Incarnation, and the Life of Jesus'', published by their Wild Goose Resource Group in 1987. \"The Summons\" has been published in many hymn books beyond the Iona Community and the United Kingdom, including those by the [[United Church of Canada]] and the [[Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/instances?qu=in%3Ainstances%20textAuthNumber%3Awill_you_come_and_follow_me&sort=hymnalTitle |title=All Instances, The Summons |publisher=Hymnary.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/hymnal/GG2013?page=7 |title=Glory to God: the Presbyterian Hymnal|publisher=Hymnary.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-30}}</ref> It also appears in \u201cWonder, Love, and Praise,\u201d the addendum hymnal of the [[Episcopal Church (United States)]].\n\n== Composition and usage ==\n\"The Summons\" is set to the tune of Kelvingrove, a traditional Scottish melody. Its text contains thirteen questions asked by Jesus in the [[grammatical person|first person]].<ref name=ion /><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.singingthefaithplus.org.uk/?p=847 |title=Where can we find you, Lord Jesus our Master?  |publisher=Methodist Church of Great Britain |date= |accessdate=2014-06-09}}</ref> The initial four stanzas with the questions are in Jesus' voice, and the fifth stanza is the singer's response to them.<ref name=hn /> The hymn is based on [[Mark 1]]:16\u201320 and alludes to Jesus calling his disciples to follow him.<ref name=ion>{{cite web|last=Vroege |first=David A. |url=http://www.reformedworship.org/article/december-2001/songs-iona |title=Songs from Iona |publisher=Reformed Worship |date= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref> C. Michael Hawn calls it a prophetic Christian hymn and mentioned that it contains words uncommon to other hymns.<ref name=gbod>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.gbod.org/lead-your-church/history-of-hymns/resource/history-of-hymns-the-summons |title=History of Hymns &#124; The Summons |publisher=GBOD |date= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref> It has been used as an example of how a Christian should react to fear and love<ref>{{cite book | first =Eva  | last =McIntyre | title =A Quiet Mind: Uniting Body, Mind and Emotions in Christian Spirituality | publisher = John Hunt Publishing | edition =  | year = 2011| isbn = 1780990057 | page = 26}}</ref> as well as being written as an example of covenantal discipleship.<ref>{{cite book | first =Kenneth  | last =Cuthbertson | title =The Last Presbyterian?: Remembering the Faith of My Forebears| publisher = Wipf and Stock Publishers | edition =  | year = 2013| isbn = 1620328704 | page = 95}}</ref> The hymn is used as a vocational and youth hymn because the words are easier to learn for younger people compared with other hymns.<ref>{{cite book | first =Tim  | last =Sledge | title =Get a Life!: Life Goals for Young People| publisher = Church House Publishing | edition =  | year = 2008| isbn = 1620328704 | page = 46}}</ref> In 2014, the hymn was used at [[Blackburn Cathedral]] at a service performed by the [[Bishop of Blackburn]] to commemorate 20 years since the first [[ordination of women in the Church of England]] as well as the [[Diocese of Blackburn]]'s decision to support the ordination of women as [[bishop]]s in the [[Church of England]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.lep.co.uk/news/special-service-to-mark-20-years-of-women-s-ministry-1-6629019 |title=Special service to mark 20 years of women\u2019s ministry  |work=Lancashire Evening Post |date= |accessdate=2014-06-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.spiritandsong.com/compositions/30338 Lyrics at ''Spirit and Song'']\n* [https://youtube.com/watch?v=TkuowlcfcOw Recording on YouTube by user DO(re)MI]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Summons, The}}\n[[Category:Scottish Christian hymns]]\n[[Category:Scottish music]]\n[[Category:1987 songs]]\n", "name_user": "Thomprod", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:added appearance in The Faith We Sing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Summons_(hymn)"}
{"title_page": "Leslie's Poolmart", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = Leslie's Poolmart, Inc.\n| logo                = Leslie's Poolmart logo.png\n| type                = [[Private company|Private]]\n| founder             = Phil Leslie\n| key_people          = \n| industry            = [[Retail]]\n| products            = Pool and spa supplies\n| owner               = [[L Catterton]]\n| homepage            = [http://www.lesliespool.com/ www.lesliespool.com]\n| foundation          = 1963<ref name=yahoo>[http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/14/14271.html Leslie's Poolmart Company Profile]  Yahoo! Business</ref>\n| location            = [[Phoenix, Arizona]]\n| locations           = 930 (2020)\n}}\n\n'''Leslie's Poolmart''', operating as '''Leslie's Swimming Pool Supplies''', is the largest retailer of swimming pool supplies and related products. Leslie's sells a full range of supplies for pool maintenance, including chemicals, cleaning devices, equipment and parts, as well as recreational and safety products for swimming pools. Leslie's also sells supplies for hot tub/spa maintenance as well as, patio and backyard furniture and accessories.\n\nThe company operates over 930 stores in 36 states throughout the U.S., with over 2,400 employees.<ref name=yahoo />  During its peak season, Leslie's employs hundreds of seasonal employees bringing its workforce above 3,000. Leslie's stocks essential pool maintenance and cleaning supplies, in addition to pool accessories and pool toys, and has more than 30,000 items available through the company's other distribution channels, such as its website and special order processes.<ref name=200910K>[https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/866048/000119312509258954/d10k.htm Leslie's Poolmart, Inc. SEC Form 10-K 2009 Annual Report].  Filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission December 23, 2009</ref>  Leslie's also sells its own brand of pool supplies, which accounted for a large portion of the company's total sales in 2009.<ref name=200910K />\n\nIn addition to pool and spa supplies, Leslie's is one of the largest retailers of pool services and repairs in the U.S.\n\nThe company is headquartered in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], and has a particularly strong retail presence in Arizona, California, Florida, Georgia and Texas.  \n\n==History==\nLeslie's was founded in 1963 by Phil Leslie, Jr. (son of Hollywood comedy writer [[Phil Leslie|Phil Leslie, Sr.]]) in a single location in [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles]]. Leslie, together with partner Raymond Cesmat, began the company by opening a chain of swimming pool supply stores in the [[Greater Los Angeles]] area.<ref name=fundinguniverse>[http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/Leslies-Poolmart-Inc-company-History.html Leslie's Poolmart, Inc.]. Funding Universe Company History</ref>\n\nThe two founding partners, Leslie and Cesmat, began fighting over the future of the company in the late 1980s, and Cesmat determined he wanted to sell his stake. In 1987, Leslie offered to buy Cesmat's stock at a prior agreed-upon price, but Cesmat would not accept. Cesmat filed to have the corporation dissolved, and in 1988, a [[California superior courts|California superior court]] judge ordered the company be sold. The company was acquired, in a hostile take-over, for $23 million by private equity firm Hancock Park Associates. Leslie received $10 million from the sale of the company but was vocal that the company had been taken from him, as the sale was highly leveraged and court-ordered.<ref name=fundinguniverse /> Following the sale of the company, managers at most Leslie's stores refused to open their stores in an expression of loyalty to Mr. Leslie. Ultimately, the new ownership and management were able to replace managers of stores that refused to open.<ref name=fundinguniverse />\n\nBy the early 1990s, the company was again generating profits, and the company listed its stock on [[NASDAQ]]. A 1991 [[initial public offering]] raised $28 million for the sale of 47% of the company, using the cash to repay debt and fund an expansion of the business.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blue blue co.|url=http://www.blueblue.co.il/|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> From the beginning of 1989 through the end of 1996, Leslie's grew from 66 to 259 company-owned and operated stores, including 23 stores added in September 1992 through the acquisition of Sandy's Pool Supply, Inc., which Mr. Leslie half-owned and had expanded from just two stores.<ref name=199610K>[https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/866048/0000898430-97-001241.txt Leslie's Poolmart, Inc. SEC Form 10-K 1996 Annual Report]. Filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission March 28, 1997</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the company was taken private for $140 million by Hancock, assisted by private equity firm [[Leonard Green & Partners]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/06/13/business/leslie-s-poolmart-taken-private-in-140-million-deal.html Leslie's Poolmart Taken Private in $140 Million Deal]. New York Times, June 13, 1997</ref> In 2010, Leonard Green explored a sale of the company targeting in excess of $1 billion for the company.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/stories/2010/07/12/daily30.html Leslie's Poolmart could make $1B+ splash]. Phoenix Business Journal, July 14, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.financierworldwide.com/article.php?id=7047 Leonard Green Seeks $1bn For Leslie's Poolmart] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426005134/http://www.financierworldwide.com/article.php?id=7047 |date=2012-04-26 }}. Financier Worldwide, July 14, 2010</ref> In lieu of a sale, Leonard Green ultimately sold a substantial stake in the company to [[CVC Capital Partners]] and [[GSO Capital Partners]].<ref>[http://www.institutionalinvestor.com/Article/2658738/CVC-Capital-To-Invest-In-Leslies.html CVC Capital To Invest In Leslie's] [https://web.archive.org/web/20130328181716/https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/Article/2658738/CVC-Capital-To-Invest-In-Leslies.html Archived copy].  Institutional Investor, August 30, 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Leslie's comprised over 750 stores, expanding to 910 by 2015. In 2017 Leslie's Poolmart was acquired by [[L Catterton]], which claims to be the largest consumer-focused private equity firm in the world.<ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/news/2017/01/17/leslies-pool-supplies-acquired-by-private-equity.html Leslie's Pool Supplies acquired by private equity firm]. Phoenix Business Journal, January 17, 2010.</ref> In February 2020, Michael Egeck assumed the role of chief executive officer.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lesliespool.com/ Leslie's Poolmart] (company website)\n\n{{Leonard Green}}\n\n[[Category:Sporting goods retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Swimming pool equipment]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1963]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Private equity portfolio companies]]\n[[Category:CVC Capital Partners companies]]\n[[Category:1997 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company \n|  name   = Leslie's Poolmart, Inc.\n|  logo   = Leslie's Poolmart logo.png\n|  type   = [[Private company|Private]]\n|  founder        = Phil Leslie\n|  key_people     = \n|  industry       = [[Retail]]\n|  products       = Pool and spa supplies\n|  owner          = [[Leonard Green & Partners]], [[CVC Capital Partners]], [[GSO Capital Partners]]\n|  homepage       = [http://www.lesliespool.com/ www.lesliespool.com]\n|  foundation     = 1963<ref name=yahoo>[http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/14/14271.html Leslie's Poolmart Company Profile]  Yahoo! Business</ref>\n|  location       = [[Phoenix, Arizona]]\n|  locations      = 910 (2015)\n}}\n\n'''Leslie's Poolmart''', operating as '''Leslie's Swimming Pool Supplies''', is the largest retailer of swimming pool supplies and related products globally.  Leslie's sells the full range of supplies for pool maintenance, including chemicals, cleaning devices, equipment and parts as well as recreational and safety products for swimming pools.  Leslie's also sells items for the backyard and patio.\n\nThe company operates over 900 stores in 35 states throughout the U.S. with over 2,400 employees.<ref name=yahoo />  During its peak season, Leslie's employs hundreds of seasonal employees bringing its workforce above 3,000. Leslie's stocks approximately 700 items in each store, with more than 30,000 additional items available through the company's other channels of distribution and special order processes.<ref name=200910K>[https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/866048/000119312509258954/d10k.htm Leslie's Poolmart, Inc. SEC Form 10-K 2009 Annual Report].  Filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission December 23, 2009</ref>  Leslie's also sells its own brand of pool supplies which accounted for 53% of the company's total sales in 2009.<ref name=200910K />\n\nThe company is headquartered in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], and has a particularly strong retail presence in Arizona, California, Florida, Georgia and Texas.  \n\n==History==\nLeslie's was founded in 1963 by Phil Leslie, Jr. (son of Hollywood comedy writer [[Phil Leslie|Phil Leslie, Sr.]]) in a single location in [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles]]. Leslie, together with partner Raymond Cesmat, began the company by opening a chain of swimming pool supply stores in the [[Greater Los Angeles]] area.<ref name=fundinguniverse>[http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/Leslies-Poolmart-Inc-company-History.html Leslie's Poolmart, Inc.]. Funding Universe Company History</ref>\n\nThe two founding partners, Leslie and Cesmat, began fighting over the future of the company in the late 1980s, and Cesmat determined he wanted to sell his stake. In 1987, Leslie offered to buy Cesmat's stock at a prior agreed-upon price, but Cesmat would not accept. Cesmat filed to have the corporation dissolved, and in 1988, a [[California superior courts|California superior court]] judge ordered the company be sold. The company was acquired, in a hostile take-over, for $23 million by private equity firm Hancock Park Associates. Leslie received $10 million from the sale of the company but was vocal that the company had been taken from him, as the sale was highly leveraged and court-ordered.<ref name=fundinguniverse /> Following the sale of the company, managers at most Leslie's stores refused to open their stores in an expression of loyalty to Mr. Leslie. Ultimately, the new ownership and management were able to replace managers of stores that refused to open.<ref name=fundinguniverse />\n\nBy the early 1990s, the company was again generating profits, and the company listed its stock on [[NASDAQ]]. A 1991 [[initial public offering]] raised $28 million for the sale of 47% of the company, using the cash to repay debt and fund an expansion of the business.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blue blue co.|url=http://www.blueblue.co.il/|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> From the beginning of 1989 through the end of 1996, Leslie's grew from 66 to 259 company-owned and operated stores, including 23 stores added in August 1992 through the acquisition of Sandy's Pool Supply, Inc., which Mr. Leslie had founded from 3 stores.<ref name=199610K>[https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/866048/0000898430-97-001241.txt Leslie's Poolmart, Inc. SEC Form 10-K 1996 Annual Report]. Filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission March 28, 1997</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the company was taken private for $140 million by Hancock, assisted by private equity firm [[Leonard Green & Partners]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/06/13/business/leslie-s-poolmart-taken-private-in-140-million-deal.html Leslie's Poolmart Taken Private in $140 Million Deal]. New York Times, June 13, 1997</ref> In 2010, Leonard Green explored a sale of the company targeting in excess of $1 billion for the company.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/stories/2010/07/12/daily30.html Leslie's Poolmart could make $1B+ splash]. Phoenix Business Journal, July 14, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.financierworldwide.com/article.php?id=7047 Leonard Green Seeks $1bn For Leslie's Poolmart] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426005134/http://www.financierworldwide.com/article.php?id=7047 |date=2012-04-26 }}. Financier Worldwide, July 14, 2010</ref> In lieu of a sale, Leonard Green ultimately sold a substantial stake in the company to [[CVC Capital Partners]] and [[GSO Capital Partners]].<ref>[http://www.institutionalinvestor.com/Article/2658738/CVC-Capital-To-Invest-In-Leslies.html CVC Capital To Invest In Leslie's] [https://web.archive.org/web/20130328181716/https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/Article/2658738/CVC-Capital-To-Invest-In-Leslies.html Archived copy].  Institutional Investor, August 30, 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Leslie's comprised over 750 stores, expanding to 910 by 2015. In 2017 Leslie's Poolmart was acquired by [[L Catterton]], which claims to be the largest consumer-focused private equity firm in the world.<ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/news/2017/01/17/leslies-pool-supplies-acquired-by-private-equity.html Leslie's Pool Supplies acquired by private equity firm]. Phoenix Business Journal, January 17, 2010.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lesliespool.com/ Leslie's Poolmart] (company website)\n\n{{Leonard Green}}\n\n[[Category:Sporting goods retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Swimming pool equipment]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1963]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Private equity portfolio companies]]\n[[Category:CVC Capital Partners companies]]\n[[Category:1997 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "Goernerlesl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changes include accuracy of Leslie's acquisition of Sandy's Pools, the addition of the newly appointed chief executive officer in 2020 and minor grammatical corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leslie%27s_Poolmart"}
{"title_page": "Celine Dion", "text_new": "{{Short description|Canadian singer}}\n{{About|the singer|her 1992 self-titled album|Celine Dion (album)}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = C\u00e9line Dion\n| honorific_suffix   = {{Post-nominals|size=100%|country=CAN|CC|OQ}}\n| image              = Celine Dion Concert Singing Taking Chances 2008.jpg\n| caption            = Dion during her [[Taking Chances World Tour]] concert in [[Bell Centre]], Montr\u00e9al, on 19 August 2008\n| birth_name         = C\u00e9line Marie Claudette Dion\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1968|3|30}}\n| birth_place        = [[Charlemagne, Quebec]], Canada\n| mother             = [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Dion|Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Tanguay Dion]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil]]<br />|17 December 1994|14 January 2016|end=died}}\n| children           = 3\n| net_worth          = $700 million<ref name=NetWorth>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6334796/madonna-paul-mccartney-worlds-richest-list|title=Celebritynetworth/Celine dion|first=Joe|last=Lynch|date=2 December 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Singer\n| years_active       = 1980\u2013present\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Celine Dion|Full list]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed           = yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[chanson]]\n*[[soft rock]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n*[[CBS Records International|CBS]]\n*[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n*[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n*[[550 Music|550]]\n*[[Legacy Recordings|Legacy]]}} <!--This is listed chronologically. PLEASE DO NOT REVERT OR CHANGE. Sony Music Canada is a division of SME and is NOT A RECORD LABEL. -->\n| associated_acts = [[David Foster]]\n| website         = {{URL|celinedion.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''C\u00e9line Marie Claudette Dion''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CC|OQ}} ({{IPAc-en|s|e\u026a|\u02cc|l|i\u02d0|n|_|d|i|\u02c8|\u0252|n}},<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ldoceonline.com/dictionary/celine-dion |title=Dion, C\u00e9line |work=[[Longman Dictionary of Contemporary English]] |publisher=[[Longman]] |accessdate=6 September 2019}}</ref> <small>also</small> {{IPAc-en|UK|-|_|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|\u0252|n}},<ref>{{cite web |title=Definition of 'Dion' |url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/dion |website=[[Collins English Dictionary]] |year=2015 |accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> {{IPA-fr|selin ma\u0281i klod\u025bt dj\u0254\u0303|lang}}, {{IPA-all|- d\u0361zj\u0254\u0303|Quebec French:}}; born 30 March 1968)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.biography.com/musician/celine-dion |title=Celine Dion |publisher=Biography.com  |access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> is a Canadian singer. Born into a large family from [[Charlemagne, Quebec]], she emerged as a teen star in her homeland with a series of French-language albums during the 1980s. She first gained international recognition by winning both the 1982 [[Yamaha (manufacturer)|Yamaha]] [[World Popular Song Festival]] and the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1988|1988 Eurovision Song Contest]], where she [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest 1988|represented Switzerland]]. After learning to speak English, she signed on to [[Epic Records]] in the United States. In 1990, Dion released her debut English-language album, ''[[Unison (Celine Dion album)|Unison]]'', establishing herself as a viable pop artist in North America and other English-speaking areas of the world.\n\nDuring the 1990s, she achieved worldwide fame after releasing several best-selling English albums, such as ''[[Falling into You]]'' (1996) and ''[[Let's Talk About Love]]'' (1997), which were both certified [[RIAA certification#RIAA Diamond certifications|diamond]] in the US. She also scored a series of international number-one hits, including \"[[The Power of Love (Jennifer Rush song)#Celine Dion version|The Power of Love]]\", \"[[Think Twice (Celine Dion song)|Think Twice]]\", \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\", \"[[It's All Coming Back to Me Now#Celine Dion|It's All Coming Back to Me Now]]\", \"[[My Heart Will Go On]]\", and \"[[I'm Your Angel]]\". Dion continued releasing French albums between each English record; ''[[D'eux]]'' (1995) became the best-selling French-language album of all time, while ''[[S'il suffisait d'aimer]]'' (1998), ''[[Sans attendre]]'' (2012), and ''[[Encore un soir]]'' (2016), were all certified [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|diamond]] in France. During the 2000s, she built her reputation as a highly successful live performer with [[A New Day...]] on the [[Las Vegas Strip]] (2003\u201307), which remains the highest-grossing [[concert residency]] of all time, as well as the [[Taking Chances World Tour]] (2008\u201309), one of the [[List of highest-grossing concert tours|highest-grossing concert tours of all time]].\n\nDion's music has been influenced by genres ranging from rock and [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] to [[Gospel music|gospel]] and [[European classical music|classical]]. Her recordings are mainly in French and English, although she also sings in Spanish, Italian, German, Latin, Japanese, and Mandarin Chinese. While her releases have often received mixed critical reception, she is regarded as one of pop music's most influential voices. She has won five [[Grammy Awards]], including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]. ''Billboard'' named her the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Queen of Adult Contemporary]]\" for having the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)#Most number-one songs|most number ones]] on the radio format for a female artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7776996/the-illustrious-career-of-celine-dion|title=Being Celine: A Look Back at the Illustrious Career of Celine Dion |work=Billboard|author=Billboard Staff|date=1 May 2017|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> She is the second best-selling female artist in the US during the [[Nielsen SoundScan]] era. In 2003, she was honoured by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI) for selling over 50 million albums in Europe. She remains the best-selling Canadian artist and [[List of best-selling music artists|one of the best-selling artists of all time]] with [[record sales]] of 200 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/celine-dion-salutes-her-gabonese-imitator-484860|title=Celine Dion Salutes Her Gabonese Imitator|last=Conor|first=Gaffey|work=[[Newsweek]] |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/music/2013/08/22/cline_dion_joins_twitter.html |title=C\u00e9line Dion joins Twitter |last=Ptashnick |first=Victoria |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=22 August 2013 |accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/music/1150596/Celine-Dion-husband-Rene-Angelil-death-career-music-tours-Hyde-Park-London|title=Celine Dion reveals 'big turnaround' since death of husband Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil: 'I'm very proud'|last=Jones|first=Louis|date=8 July 2019|website=Express|language=en|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===1968\u20131989: Early life and career beginnings===\nDion was born in [[Charlemagne, Quebec]], {{convert|15|mi|km|order=flip}} northeast of [[Montreal]], the youngest of 14 children of [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Dion|Th\u00e9r\u00e8se]] (n\u00e9e Tanguay, 1927\u20132020), a homemaker, and Adh\u00e9mar Dion (1923\u20132003), a butcher, both of French-Canadian descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perche-quebec.com/files/celine/individus/celine_en.htm|title=Celine Dion: From the Perche (France) to Las Vegas|accessdate=23 January 2016|website=perche-quebec.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513183630/http://www.perche-quebec.com/files/celine/individus/celine_en.htm|archive-date=13 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/75/Celine-Dion.html|title=Celine Dion Biography|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> She was raised a Roman Catholic in a poor, but, by her own account, happy home in Charlemagne.<ref name=\"CNNN\">{{cite news|title=The 'ultimate diva'|url=http://edition.cnn.com/CNN/Programs/people/shows/dion/profile.html|work=[[People in the News]]|publisher=CNN|accessdate=25 September 2013|date=22 October 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated12\">\"Profiles of Celine Dion, Enrique Iglesias, Moby\". Paula Zahn, Charles Molineaux, Gail O'Neill. ''[[People in the News]]'', 18 May 2002. Transcript.</ref> Music had always been a major part of the Dion family, and she was named after the song \"C\u00e9line\", which French singer [[Hugues Aufray]] had recorded two years before her own birth.<ref>{{cite book|first=Georges-Herbert|last=Germain|others=translated by David Homel and Fred Reed|year=1998|title=C\u00e9line: The Authorized Biography|page=[https://archive.org/details/celineauthorized0000germ/page/16 16]|publisher=[[Dundurn Press]]|isbn=978-1-55002-318-3|url=https://archive.org/details/celineauthorized0000germ/page/16}}</ref> On 13 August 1973, at the age of five, the young C\u00e9line made her first public appearance at her brother Michel's wedding, where she performed [[Christine Charbonneau]]'s song \"Du fil des aiguilles et du coton\".<ref>{{cite web|author=jmaster|url=http://www.portrait-star.fr/st-celine-dion.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405132148/http://www.portrait-star.fr/st-celine-dion.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 April 2012|title=C\u00e9line Dion Biography|publisher=Portrait-star.fr|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> She continued to perform with her siblings in her parents' small [[piano bar]] called ''Le Vieux Baril'', \"The Old Barrel\". From an early age, she had dreamed of being a performer.<ref name=Time1>{{cite news|last=Alexander|first=Charles P.|title=The Power of Celine Dion|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,980285,00.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=7 March 2004|accessdate=25 September 2013}} {{registration required}}</ref> In a 1994 interview with ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, she recalled, \"I missed my family and my home, but I don't regret having lost my adolescence. I had one dream: I wanted to be a singer.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Sanz|first=Cynthia|title=North Star|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20108321,00.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021042024/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C20108321%2C00.html|archive-date=21 October 2012|publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=13 June 1994|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:C\u00e9line Dion 1986.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Dion at the age of 18]]\n\nAt age 12, she collaborated with her mother and her brother Jacques to write and compose her first song, \"[[Ce n'\u00e9tait qu'un r\u00eave]]\", whose title translates as \"It Was Only a Dream\" or \"Nothing But A Dream\".<ref name=\"autogenerated12\"/> Her brother Michel sent the recording to music manager [[Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil]], whose name he discovered on the back of a [[Ginette Reno]] album.<ref name=\"Jam\">{{cite web|title=Dion, Celine|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Pop_Encyclopedia/D/Dion_Celine.html|work=[[Jam!]]|publisher=Canoe.ca|accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref> Ang\u00e9lil was moved to tears by Dion's voice and decided to make her a star.<ref name=\"autogenerated12\"/> In 1981, he mortgaged his home to fund her first record, ''[[La voix du bon Dieu]]'', which later became a local No. 1 hit and made her an instant star in Quebec. Her popularity spread to other parts of the world when she competed in the 1982 Yamaha World Popular Song Festival in [[Tokyo, Japan]], and won the musician's award for \"Top Performer\" as well as the gold medal for \"Best Song\" with \"[[Tellement j'ai d'amour pour toi]]\".<ref name=\"Jam\"/>\n\nBy 1983, in addition to becoming the first Canadian artist to receive a gold record in France for the single \"[[D'amour ou d'amiti\u00e9]]\" (\"Of Love or of Friendship\"), Dion had also won several [[F\u00e9lix Award]]s, including \"Best Female performer\" and \"Discovery of the Year\".<ref name=\"Jam\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated20\">[http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/celine-dion.html Celine Dion Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927104806/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/celine-dion.html |date=27 September 2013 }}, [[The Biography Channel]]. 13 September 2007.</ref> Further success came when she represented [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Switzerland]] in the [[1988 Eurovision Song Contest]] with the song \"[[Ne partez pas sans moi]]\" and won the contest by a close margin in [[Dublin]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Connor|first=John Kennedy|title=The Eurovision Song Contest&nbsp;\u2014 The Official History|authorlink=John Kennedy O'Connor|publisher=[[Carlton Books]]|location=UK|date=2 April 2007|isbn=978-1-84442-994-3}}</ref>\n\nAt age eighteen, after seeing a [[Michael Jackson]] performance, Dion told Ang\u00e9lil that she wanted to be a star like Jackson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/az/dion_celine/artist.jhtml#biographyEnd|title=''C\u00e9line Dion''|work=MTV Artists|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Though confident in her talent, Ang\u00e9lil realized that her image needed to be changed for her to be marketed worldwide.<ref name=\"autogenerated12\"/> She receded from the spotlight for a number of months, during which she underwent dental surgery to improve her appearance, and was sent to the [[Berlitz Corporation|\u00c9cole Berlitz]] in 1989 to polish her English.<ref name=Enc>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/emc/celine-dion|encyclopedia=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=[[Historica-Dominion]]|accessdate=25 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927173706/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/emc/celine-dion|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, during a concert on the [[Incognito tourn\u00e9e]], she injured her voice. She consulted the [[Otolaryngology|otorhinolaryngologist]] William Gould,<ref name=\"Bombardier 2009 172\u2013173\">{{cite book|first=Denise|last=Bombardier|title=L'\u00e9nigmatique C\u00e9line Dion|publisher=Albin Michel, XO \u00e9ditions|year=2009|pages=[https://archive.org/details/lenigmatiqueceli0000bomb/page/172 172\u201373]|isbn=978-2-84563-413-8|language=French|url=https://archive.org/details/lenigmatiqueceli0000bomb/page/172}}</ref><ref name=\"Germain p. 279-280\">Germain, Georges-H\u00e9bert (2010). ''Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil: Derri\u00e8re le conte de f\u00e9es'', Michel Lafon. pp. 279\u2013280.<!--ISSN/ISBN needed--></ref> who gave her an ultimatum: have immediate surgery on her [[vocal cords]] or do not utilize them at all for three weeks.<ref name=\"Bombardier 2009 172\u2013173\"/> Dion chose the latter and underwent vocal training with William Riley.<ref name=\"Bombardier 2009 172\u2013173\"/><ref name=\"Germain p. 279-280\"/>\n\n===1990\u20131992: ''Unison'', ''Dion chante Plamondon'' and ''Celine Dion''===\nTwo years after she learned English, Dion made her debut into the Anglophone market with ''[[Unison (Celine Dion album)|Unison]]'' (1990), the lead single having originally been recorded by [[Laura Branigan]].<ref name=\"Jam\"/> She incorporated the help of many established musicians, including Vito Luprano and Canadian producer [[David Foster]].<ref name=\"Time1\"/> The album was largely influenced by 1980s [[soft rock]] music that quickly found a niche within the [[adult contemporary]] radio format. ''Unison'' also hit the right notes with critics: Jim Faber of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that her vocals were \"tastefully unadorned\", and that she never attempted to \"bring off styles that are beyond her\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Review\u2014C\u00e9line Dion Unison|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/review/music/0,6115,313100_4_0_,00.html|accessdate=10 February 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625165657/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C313100%2C00.html|archivedate=25 June 2009|date=25 January 1991|last=Farber|first=Jim|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] declared it \"a fine, sophisticated American debut\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Allmusic|work=Review\u2014C\u00e9line Dion Unison|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r5855|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=18 November 2005}}</ref> Singles from the album included \"[[(If There Was) Any Other Way]]\", \"[[The Last to Know]]\", \"[[Unison (song)#C\u00e9line Dion version|Unison]]\", and \"[[Where Does My Heart Beat Now]]\", a mid-tempo soft-rock ballad that made prominent use of the electric guitar. The latter became her first top-ten hit on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], peaking at number four. In 1991, Dion was a featured soloist on \"[[Voices That Care]]\", a tribute to American troops fighting in [[Operation Desert Storm]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nHer real international breakthrough came when she duetted with [[Peabo Bryson]] on the [[Beauty and the Beast (Disney song)|title track]] to [[Disney]]'s animated film ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (1991).<ref name=autogenerated8>{{cite news|last=Bliss|first=Karen|title=25 Years of Canadian Artists |work=Canadian Musician |date=1 March 2004 |page=34 |issn=0708-9635}}</ref> It became her first top-ten hit in the UK and her second top-ten hit in the US. The song earned its songwriters an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Song]] and gave Dion her first [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]].<ref name=\"Time1\"/> \"Beauty and the Beast\" served as the [[lead single]] from her 1992 [[Celine Dion (album)|self-titled album]], which, like her debut, had a strong pop rock influence combined with elements of soul and classical music. Owing to the success of the lead-off single and her collaborations with David Foster and [[Diane Warren]], the album was even more well-received commercially than ''Unison''; it was certified diamond in Canada and double platinum in the US. The album's second single \"[[If You Asked Me To#C\u00e9line Dion version|If You Asked Me To]]\" (a [[cover version|cover]] of [[Patti LaBelle]]'s song from the 1989 movie ''[[Licence to Kill]]'') became her first [[List of number-one singles of 1992 (Canada)|number-one single]] in Canada and peaked at number four on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\nAlso during this time, Dion released the Francophone album ''[[Dion chante Plamondon]]''. The album consisted mostly of covers, but featured four new songs: \"[[Des mots qui sonnent (song)|Des mots qui sonnent]]\", \"[[Je danse dans ma t\u00eate]]\", \"[[Quelqu'un que j'aime, quelqu'un qui m'aime]]\" and \"[[L'amour existe encore]]\". It was originally released in Canada and France during the 1991\u20131992 period, then later received an international release in 1994, the first French Celine Dion album to do so. \"[[Un gar\u00e7on pas comme les autres (Ziggy)]]\" became a smash hit in France, reaching No. 2 and being certified gold. In Quebec, the album was certified Gold the day it was released.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nBy 1992, ''Unison'', ''C\u00e9line Dion'', and numerous high-profile media appearances had propelled Dion to superstardom in North America. She had achieved one of her main objectives: wedging her way into the Anglophone market and achieving fame.<ref name=\"autogenerated18\">Alexander, Charles P. \"The Arts & Media/Music: At Age Five She Belted Out French pop tunes standing atop tables\". ''Time International''. 28 February 1994. pg 44.</ref> However, while she was experiencing rising success in the US, her French fans in Canada criticized her for neglecting them.<ref name=\"Time1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated21\">\"Celine Dion\". ''Newsmakers 1995'', Issue 4. Gale Research, 1995.</ref> She would later rebuff these criticisms at the 1991 [[F\u00e9lix Awards]] show, where, after winning \"English Artist of the Year\", she openly refused to accept the award. She asserted that she was\u2014and would always be\u2014a French, not an English, artist.<ref name= Enc/><ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion|work=Biography|url=http://www.celinedionweb.com/celine-dion/en,biography.html|accessdate=26 April 2006}}</ref> Apart from her commercial success, there were also changes in her personal life, as Ang\u00e9lil, who was twenty-six years her senior, transitioned from manager to lover. However, the relationship was kept a secret as they both feared that the public would find their relations inappropriate.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\">\"Celine Dion\". ''Contemporary Musicians, Volume 25''. Gale Group, 1999.<!-- ISSN/ISBN, page(s) needed --></ref>\n\n===1993\u20131995: ''The Colour of My Love'' and ''D'eux''===\n[[File:Dion C ter.jpg|thumb|upright|Celine Dion reading a magazine in 1994.]]\nIn 1993, Dion announced her feelings for her manager by declaring him \"the colour of [her] love\" in the dedication section of her third English-language album ''[[The Colour of My Love]]''. However, instead of criticizing their relationship as she had feared, fans embraced the couple.<ref name=\"Time1\"/> Eventually, Ang\u00e9lil and Dion married in an extravagant wedding ceremony in December 1994, which was broadcast live on Canadian television.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAs with most of her catalogue, ''The Colour of My Love'' had over-riding themes of love and romance.<ref name=\"autogenerated23\">{{cite web|title=Celine Dion The Colour of My Love|url=http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2002/celinedion-thecolourofmylove.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402231118/http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2002/celinedion-thecolourofmylove.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 April 2012|work=Plugged In|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> It became her most successful record up to that point, selling more than six million copies in the US, two million in Canada, and peaking at No. 1 in many countries. The album also spawned Dion's first US, Canadian, and Australian No. 1 single \"[[The Power of Love (Celine Dion)|The Power of Love]]\" (a remake of [[Jennifer Rush]]'s 1985 hit), which would become her [[signature song|signature hit]] until she reached new career heights in the late 1990s.<ref name=\"autogenerated18\"/>\n\nThe single \"[[When I Fall in Love#C\u00e9line Dion and Clive Griffin version|When I Fall in Love]]\", a [[duet]] with [[Clive Griffin]], achieved moderate success on the US and Canadian charts and was nominated for two Grammy Awards, winning one. ''The Colour of My Love'' also became Dion's first major hit in Europe, particularly in the United Kingdom. Both the album and the single \"[[Think Twice (Celine Dion song)|Think Twice]]\" simultaneously occupied the top of the British charts for five consecutive weeks. \"Think Twice\", which remained at No. 1 for seven weeks, eventually became the fourth single by a female artist to sell in excess of one million copies in the UK<ref>{{cite web|work=Celinedion.com|title=The Journey so Far|url=http://www.celinedion.com/biography?page=0,2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709112546/http://www.celinedion.com/biography?page=0%2C2|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 July 2012|accessdate=16 August 2005}}</ref> while the album was eventually certified five-times platinum for two million copies sold.<ref>[http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115055129/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|date=15 January 2013|title=Certified Awards Search}}</ref>\n\nDion kept to her French roots and continued to release many Francophone recordings between each English record.<ref name=\"autogenerated15\">\"Celine Dion\". Compton's by Britannica. ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica''. 2005.</ref> Generally, they achieved more credibility than her English-language works.<ref name=\"autogenerated21\"/> She released ''[[\u00c0 l'Olympia (C\u00e9line Dion album)|\u00c0 l'Olympia]]'', a live album that was recorded during one of her concerts at the [[Paris Olympia]] in 1994. It had one promotional single, a live version of \"[[Calling You#C\u00e9line Dion version|Calling You]]\", which peaked at seventy-five on the French Singles Chart. She also recorded a bilingual version of \"[[Petit Papa No\u00ebl]]\" with [[Alvin and the Chipmunks]] for the 1994 holiday album ''[[A Very Merry Chipmunk]]''. ''[[D'eux]]'' (also known as ''The French Album'' in the United States), was released in 1995, and it would go on to become the best-selling French-language album of all time.<ref name=\"autogenerated15\"/> The album was mostly written and produced by [[Jean-Jacques Goldman]], and amassed huge success with the singles \"[[Pour que tu m'aimes encore]]\" and \"[[Je sais pas]]\". \"Pour que tu m'aimes encore\" reached No. 1 in France and stayed at the top position for twelve weeks. It was later certified Platinum in France.<ref>[http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/monopage.xml?id=259165&year=1995&type=9 Celine Dion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111014755/http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/monopage.xml?id=259165&year=1995&type=9|date=11 January 2012}}; retrieved 12 October 2009.</ref> The single reached the top ten in the UK and Ireland, a rare accomplishment for a French song. The second single off the album, \"Je sais pas\", reached No. 1 on the French Singles Chart as well and was certified Silver there.<ref>{{cite web|title=Les disques d'or|url=http://www.snepmusique.com/fr/monopage.xml?id=259165&year=1995&type=6|accessdate=27 September 2013|language=French|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011202015/http://www.snepmusique.com/fr/monopage.xml?id=259165&year=1995&type=6|archivedate=11 October 2012}}</ref> These songs later became \"If That's What It Takes\" and \"I Don't Know\" on her next English album, ''[[Falling into You]]''.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nDuring the mid-1990s and onward, Dion's albums were generally constructed on the basis of melodramatic soft rock ballads, with sprinklings of up-tempo pop and rare forays into other genres.<ref>[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine|Erlewine, Stephen Thomas]]. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r328599|pure_url=yes}} Let's Talk About Love: Album review]. Allmusic; retrieved 12 October 2009.</ref> She collaborated with many renowned writers and producers such as Jim Steinman and David Foster, who helped her to develop a signature sound.<ref name=\"Time1\"/><ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r232836|pure_url=yes}} AllMusic.com; retrieved 12 October 2009.</ref> While critical reviews fluctuated, her releases performed increasingly well on the international charts, and in 1996, she won the [[World Music Award]] for \"World's Best-selling Female Recording Artist of the Year\" for the third time. By the mid-1990s, she had established herself as one of the [[List of best-selling music artists|best-selling artists in the world]].<ref name=Inter>Jerome, Jim. \"The Dream That Drives Her. (Singer Celine Dion) (Interview)\", ''Ladies Home Journal'', 1 November 1997. 146(4).</ref>\n\n===1996\u20131999: ''Falling into You'', ''Let's Talk About Love'' and ''S'il suffisait d'aimer''===\n<!--\n{{Listen\n | filename = CelineDionFallingIntoYou.ogg\n | title = \"Falling into You\" (1996)\n | description = The title track was noted for its considerable use of percussion instruments and the saxophone.\n | filename2 = CelineDionCalltheMan.ogg\n | title2 = \"Call the Man\" (1996)\n | description2 = One of the final tracks on the album, \"[[Call the Man]]\", features a [[choir]] chanting and humming in an African language.\n | filename3 = IDon'tKnowCelineDion.ogg\n | title3 = \"I Don't Know\" (1996)\n | description3 = ''Falling into You'' contained outlandish musical effects, as epitomized by the single \"I Don't Know\".\n | pos=left\n | header= Musical diversity of ''Falling into You''\n }}\n{{Listen\n | filename = On Ne Change Pas - C\u00e9line Dion.ogg\n | title = \"On ne change pas\" (\"''We don't change''\") (1998)\n | description = This song's theme is centred on childhood memories (esp. from C\u00e9line's childhood in [[Charlemagne, Quebec|Charlemagne]], Canada) and how people's \"inner child\" remains.\n | pos=right\n | header= From the ''On ne change pas'' album\n }}\n-->\n''[[Falling into You]]'' (1996), Dion's fourth English-language album, presented the singer at the height of her popularity and showed a further progression of her music.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/> In an attempt to reach a wider audience, the album combined many elements, such as complex orchestral sounds, African [[chanting]], and elaborate musical effects. Additionally, instruments like the violin, [[Classical guitar|Spanish guitar]], [[trombone]], the [[cavaquinho]], and saxophone created a new sound.<ref name=\"autogenerated17\">{{cite news|title=Entertainment Weekly|work=Review --Falling into You|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/review/music/0,6115,291693_4_0_,00.html|accessdate=14 July 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105235656/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C291693%2C00.html|archivedate=5 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The singles encompassed a variety of musical styles. The title track \"[[Falling into You (song)|Falling into You]]\" and \"[[River Deep \u2013 Mountain High]]\" (a [[Tina Turner]] cover) made prominent use of percussion instruments; \"[[It's All Coming Back to Me Now#C\u00e9line Dion|It's All Coming Back to Me Now]]\" (produced by its writer [[Jim Steinman]]) and a remake of [[Eric Carmen]]'s \"[[All by Myself#C\u00e9line Dion version|All by Myself]]\" maintained a soft-rock atmosphere, combined with the classical sound of the piano; and the No. 1 single \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\", which was written by Diane Warren, was a pop ballad that served as the theme to the 1996 film ''[[Up Close and Personal (film)|Up Close and Personal]]''.<ref name=\"Inter\"/>\n\n''Falling into You'' garnered career-best reviews for Dion. While Dan Leroy wrote that it was not very different from her previous work,<ref>{{cite web|author=Leroy, Dan|work=Yahoo Music|title=Album Review: Falling into You|url=http://music.uk.launch.yahoo.com/read/review/12030099|date=12 March 1996|accessdate=1 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120708214631/http://music.uk.launch.yahoo.com/read/review/12030099|archivedate=8 July 2012}}</ref> and Stephen Holden of ''[[The New York Times]]'' and Natalie Nichols of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote that the album was formulaic,<ref>Stephen, Holden. ''Review: Falling into you''. ''[[The New York Times]]''. (Late Edition (East Coast)). New York: 14 April 1996.</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">Nichols, Natalie. ''Pop music review: The Grammy Winner is Charming At the Universal Amphitheatre But Her Singing Still Lacks Emotional Connection''. ''Los Angeles Times''. Los Angeles: 27 March 1997. p. 47</ref> other critics, such as Chuck Eddy of ''Entertainment Weekly'', Stephen Thomas Erlewine of AllMusic, and Daniel Durchholz, lavished the album as \"compelling\", \"passionate\", \"stylish\", \"elegant\", and \"remarkably well-crafted\".<ref name=\"autogenerated17\"/><ref>{{cite web | title=Allmusic| work=Review --Falling into You| url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r232836|pure_url=yes}}| accessdate=1 November 2005 }}</ref> ''Falling into You'' became Dion's most critically and commercially successful album: it topped the charts in many countries and became one of the best-selling albums of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Angelfire.com| work=C\u00e9line Dion Discography|url=http://www.angelfire.com/pop/divacelinedion/Sales.html|accessdate=1 November 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[CBC Music]] ranked ''Falling into You'' 33rd in their list of the 100 greatest Canadian albums ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.cbc.ca/#/blogs/2013/7/100-greatest-Canadian-albums-ever-40-21|title=CBC Music|publisher=Music.cbc.ca|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301002442/http://music.cbc.ca/#/blogs/2013/7/100-greatest-Canadian-albums-ever-40-21|archivedate=1 March 2016}}</ref> In the United States, the album reached No. 1,<ref name=\"mtv.com\">{{cite news|last=Basham|first=David|title=Got Charts? Wrestling With WWF LPs; Breaking Records With Celine|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453281/got-charts-wwf-celine-dion.jhtml|accessdate=27 September 2013|newspaper=[[MTV News]]|date=5 April 2002}}</ref> and was later certified 11\u00d7 Platinum for over 11 million copies shipped.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblTop100|title=Falling into you|publisher=Riaa.com|accessdate=19 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701162536/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblTop100|archivedate=1 July 2007}}</ref> In Canada, the album was certified diamond for over one million copies shipped.<ref>[http://cria.ca/cert_db_search.php Search Certification Database] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019175407/http://cria.ca/cert_db_search.php|date=19 October 2010}} CRIA.ca; retrieved 31 December 2009.</ref> The [[IFPI]] certified ''Falling into You'' 9\u00d7 Platinum, an accolade that has been given to only two other albums in history, with one of the two being Dion's own album, ''[[Let's Talk About Love]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/platinum-europe-awards-2007.pdf|title=IFPI Platinum Europe Awards|publisher=IFPI|year=2009|accessdate=7 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725051454/http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/platinum-europe-awards-2007.pdf|archive-date=25 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album also won [[Grammy Award]]s for [[Best Pop Album]] and the academy's highest honour, [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Biography|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/music/artist/bio/0,,423645,00.html|work=ARTISTdirect|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nDion was asked to perform \"[[The Power of the Dream]]\" at the opening ceremony of the 1996 [[Atlanta Olympic Games]].<ref>Carwell, Nikea. \"Over the Years\", ''Variety'', 13 November 2000, pg. 66. vol 380; No. 13 {{ISSN|0042-2738}}.</ref> In March 1996, she launched the [[Falling into You Tour]] in support of her new album, performing concerts around the world for over a year.\n[[File:Celine Dion by Linda Bisset.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Celine Dion during the promotion of ''[[Let's Talk About Love]]'', 1998.]] She followed ''Falling into You'' with ''[[Let's Talk About Love]]'' (1997), which was publicized as its sequel.<ref name=\"autogenerated13\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r328599|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=AllMusic Guide|title=Review- Let's Talk About Love|year=2007|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> The recording process took place in London, New York City, and Los Angeles, and featured a host of special guests, such as [[Barbra Streisand]] on \"[[Tell Him (Barbra Streisand and Celine Dion song)|Tell Him]]\"; the [[Bee Gees]] on \"[[Immortality (Celine Dion song)|Immortality]]\"; and [[tenor]] [[Luciano Pavarotti]] on \"[[I Hate You Then I Love You]]\".<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/><ref name= archives>{{cite web|url=http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2002/celinedion-letstalkaboutlove.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715094203/http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2002/CelineDion-LetsTalkAboutLove.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 July 2011|title=Celine Dion, Let's Talk About Love|work=plugged in.com|publisher=Focus on the Family|year=2009|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> Other musicians included [[Carole King]], [[George Martin|Sir George Martin]], [[Bryan Adams]] and Jamaican singer [[Diana King]], who added a [[Reggae fusion|reggae tinge]] to \"[[Treat Her Like a Lady (Celine Dion song)|Treat Her Like a Lady]]\"<ref>C\u00e9line Dion, at ''Junior Canadian Encyclopedia (2002)''. [[Historica Canada]]. 2002.</ref>\n\n''Let's Talk About Love'' was another major success, reaching No.&nbsp;1 all over the world, attaining platinum status in twenty-four sales territories, and becoming the fastest selling album of her career.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=q1Q8PlAnosQC&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52|title=Titanic: anatomy of a blockbuster|first1=Kevin S.|last1=Sandler|first2=Gaylyn|last2=Studlar|publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]]|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8135-2669-0}}</ref> In the United States, the album topped the chart in its seventh week of release,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/album/1503022/lets-talk-about-love|title=Let's Talk About Love \u2013 Celine Dion|publisher=Billboard music charts|year=2009|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> and was later certified 10\u00d7 Platinum in the US for over 10 million copies shipped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.org/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524143006/http://riaa.org/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 May 2012|title=GOLD & PLATINUM certification|publisher=Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA)|year=2009|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> In Canada, the album sold 230,212 copies in its first week of release, which remains a record.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Mw0EAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&q=Let's%20Talk%20About%20Love|title=Billboard 26 December 1998\u20132 January 1999|publisher=Billboard music charts|year=2009}}</ref> It was eventually certified diamond in Canada for over one million copies shipped.<ref>[http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php Search Certification Database] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501065534/http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php|date=1 May 2010}} CRIA.ca; retrieved 31 December 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Mw0EAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Let's%20Talk%20About%20Love|title=Billboard Magazine|accessdate=27 September 2014|date=2 January 1999}}</ref> The most successful single from the album was the [[classical music|classically]] influenced ballad \"[[My Heart Will Go On]]\", which was written and composed by [[James Horner]] and [[Will Jennings]], and produced by Horner and [[Walter Afanasieff]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>\n\nServing as the love theme for the 1997 blockbuster film ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'', the song topped the charts across the world and became Dion's [[signature song]].<ref name=\"autogenerated19\">{{cite journal|author=Weatherford, Mike|title=Show review: As Dion feels more comfortable, her show improves|website=Reviewjournal.com|year=2004|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/Oct-01-Fri-2004/weekly/24865136.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041012071727/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/Oct-01-Fri-2004/weekly/24865136.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 October 2004}}</ref> Horner and Jennings won the [[Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]],<ref>[http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/29146 My Heart Will Go On], Goldenglobes.org; retrieved 22 October 2009. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919221454/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/29146|date=19 September 2012}}</ref> while Dion herself garnered two Grammy Awards for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]] and the most coveted, [[Record of the Year]], (the song itself won four awards, but two were presented to the songwriters).<ref>{{cite news|title=That thing: Lauryn Hill sets Grammy record|url=http://edition.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Music/9902/24/grammy/index.html|accessdate=27 September 2013|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=24 February 1999}}</ref> \"My Heart Will Go On\" and \"Think Twice\" made her the only female artist in the UK to have two singles to sell more than a million copies.<ref name=jealous>{{cite web|last=Iley|first=Chrissy|title=People are jealous|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/dec/10/popandrock1|work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 September 2013|date=10 December 2007}}</ref> In support of her album, she embarked on the [[Let's Talk About Love Tour]] between 1998 and 1999.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5919196/babs_pavarotti_others_may_sing_with_celine/print |title=Babs, Pavarotti, Others May Sing With Celine|journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=6 August 1998 |accessdate=29 July 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224033306/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5919196/babs_pavarotti_others_may_sing_with_celine/print|archivedate=24 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDion ended the 1990s with three more extremely successful albums: the [[Christmas music|Christmas album]] ''[[These Are Special Times]]'' (1998), the French-language album, ''[[S'il suffisait d'aimer]]'', and the compilation album ''[[All the Way... A Decade of Song]]'' (1999).<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">Taylor, Chuck. \"Epic/550's Dion offers Hits\", ''Billboard'', 6 November 1999. pg. 1.</ref> On ''These Are Special Times'', she co-wrote the song \"Don't Save It All for Christmas Day\" along with [[Ric Wake]] and Peter Zizzo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/these-are-special-times-mw0000601239|title=These Are Special Times Review|work=AllMusic|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> The album was her most classically influenced yet, with orchestral arrangements found on virtually every track.<ref>Lewis, Randy. \"Album Review/Pop; Celine Dion Aims to Be the Christmas Star; ''These Are Special Times'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (page F-28), October 1998.</ref> The album featured the single \"[[I'm Your Angel]]\" (a [[duet]] with [[R. Kelly]]), which became her fourth US No. 1 single, and a smash hit across the world. The album's second single \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" (a duet with [[Andrea Bocelli]]) served as the soundtrack of the 1998 film ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'' and won a Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song. ''All the Way... A Decade of Song'' drew together her most successful hits coupled with seven new songs, including the lead-off single \"[[That's the Way It Is (Celine Dion song)|That's the Way It Is]]\", a cover of [[Roberta Flack]]'s \"[[The First Time Ever I Saw Your Face]]\", and \"[[All the Way (Frank Sinatra song)|All the Way]]\", a duet with [[Frank Sinatra]].<ref name=\"autogenerated4\"/> ''All the Way'' became one of the best-selling compilation albums of all time, reaching No. 1 in the United States for three weeks.<ref name=\"mtv.com\"/> The album was later certified 7x Platinum in the US for 7 million copies shipped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.org/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524143006/http://riaa.org/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 May 2012|title=GOLD & PLATINUM|publisher=Riaa.org|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> It also topped the charts in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.co.uk/|title=UK Top 40 Hit Database|publisher=Everyhit.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Canada,<ref name=\"Jam! Showbiz\">{{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music|title=Jam! Showbiz|publisher=Jam.canoe.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=C%E9line+Dion&titel=All+The+Way%2E%2E%2E+A+Decade+Of+Song&cat=a|title=C\u00c9LINE DION \u2013 ALL THE WAY... A DECADE OF SONG (ALBUM)|publisher=Australian-charts.com|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> Her last French-language studio album of the 1990s, ''S'il suffisait d'aimer'', was very successful as well, topping the charts in every major French-speaking country, including France,<ref>[http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=C%E9line+Dion&titel=S%27il+suffisait+d%27aimer&cat=a French Albums Chart], LesCharts.com; retrieved 31 December 2009.</ref> Switzerland,<ref>[http://hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?interpret=C%E9line+Dion&titel=S%27il+suffisait+d%27aimer&cat=a Swiss Albums Chart] ''Hit Parade''; accessed 27 June 2017.</ref> the Wallonia region of Belgium,<ref>[http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=C%E9line+Dion&titel=S%27il+suffisait+d%27aimer&cat=a C\u00c9LINE DION \u2013 S'IL SUFFISAIT D'AIMER (ALBUM)], UltraTop.be; retrieved 31 December 2009.{{in lang|fr}}</ref> and Canada.<ref name=\"Jam! Showbiz\"/> In France, the album was certified diamond, selling 1.5&nbsp;million copies.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111212161548/http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/page-259165.xml?id=259165&year=1998 LES CERTIFICATIONS], disqueenfrance.com; retrieved 31 December 2009.</ref> By the end of the 1990s, Dion had sold more than 100 million albums worldwide, and had won a slew of industry awards.<ref name=autogenerated3>Taylor, Chuck. \"Epic/550's Dion offers Hits\". ''Billboard''. 6 November 1999. p. 1</ref> Her status as one of the music industry's biggest pop divas was further solidified when she was asked to perform on [[VH1]]'s ''Divas Live'' special in 1998, with superstars [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Gloria Estefan]], [[Shania Twain]], and [[Mariah Carey]].<ref>Macdonald, Patrick (8 October 1998) [http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19981008&slug=2776388 \"The Unsinkable Celine Dion \u2013 Pop Diva Is On Top Of The World, And Not Even An Iceberg Could Stop Her Now\"], ''[[Seattle Times]]''; retrieved 22 October 2009.</ref> That year, she also received two of the highest Canadian honours: \"Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] for Outstanding Contribution to the World of Contemporary Music\"<ref name=\"gg.ca\"/><ref name=\"gazette.gc.ca\"/> and \"Officer of the [[National Order of Quebec]]\".<ref name=\"ordre-national.gouv.qc.ca\"/> A year later, she was inducted into the [[Canadian Broadcast Hall of Fame]], and was honoured with a star on [[Canada's Walk of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=canadaswalkoffame.com|work=Canada's Walk of Fame|url=http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com|accessdate=30 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nStarting from the mid-1990s, the [[pop rock]] influence that was more noticeable in her earlier releases was replaced by a more mature feel.<ref name=\"autogenerated13\"/> Additionally, the recurring theme of \"love\" dominated most of her releases, which led to some critics dismissing her music as banal.<ref name=\"autogenerated24\">{{cite news|title=findarticles.com |work=The unsinkable C\u00e9line Dion&nbsp;\u2014 French-Canadian singer&nbsp;\u2014 Interview |url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_3_29/ai_54133689 |accessdate=5 December 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050408032911/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_3_29/ai_54133689 |archivedate=8 April 2005}}</ref> Other critics, like Elysa Gardner and Jose F. Promis, praised her voice during this period, describing it as a \"technical marvel\".<ref>Gardner, Elysa. \"Review: Falling Into You\". ''Los Angeles Times'': 16 November 1997, p. 68</ref><ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r367753|pure_url=yes}} A l'Olympia Celine Dion] AllMusic. Retrieved 27 February 2010.</ref> Steve Dollar, in his review of ''These Are Special Times'', opined that Dion was a \"vocal Olympian for whom there ain't no mountain\u2014or scale\u2014high enough\".<ref>Dollar, Steve. \"Review: These Are Special Times\", ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'', pg. C01, 3 November 1998.</ref>\n\n===2000\u20132003: Hiatus, ''A New Day Has Come'', ''One Heart'' and ''1 fille & 4 types''===\n[[File:Celine Dion 2000.jpg|thumb|upright|Dion in 2000]]\nAfter releasing and promoting thirteen albums during the 1990s, Dion stated that she needed to settle down, and announced on her latest album ''[[All the Way... A Decade of Song]]'', that she needed to take a step back from the spotlight and enjoy life.<ref name=\"CNNN\"/><ref name=vh1>{{cite web|title=VH1|work=C\u00e9line Dion: Let's Talk About Success: The Singer Explains Her Career High-Points|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1453531/04222002/dion_celine.jhtml|accessdate=19 December 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050330094606/http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1453531/04222002/dion_celine.jhtml|archivedate=30 March 2005}}</ref> Ang\u00e9lil's diagnosis with [[esophageal cancer]] also prompted her to hiatus.<ref>King, Larry. ''[[Larry King Live]]''. Personal Interview Interview With Celine Dion. [[CNN]]. 26 March 2002.</ref> While on break, she was unable to escape the spotlight. In 2000, the ''[[National Enquirer]]'' published a false story about the singer. Brandishing a picture of Dion and her husband, the magazine misquoted her, printing the headline, \"Celine&nbsp;\u2014 'I'm Pregnant With Twins!'\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/661089.stm|title=BBC News|publisher=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> She later sued the magazine for more than $20{{nbsp}}million.<ref>[http://www.courttv.com/archive/people/2000/0229/celine_ap.html \"Celine Dion Sues ''National Enquirer'' Over Twin Pregnancy Story\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229092749/http://www.courttv.com/archive/people/2000/0229/celine_ap.html |date=29 December 2008 }}, courttv.com, 29 February 2000; retrieved 15 May 2007.</ref> The editors of the ''Enquirer'' printed an apology and a full retraction to her in the next issue, and donated money to the [[American Cancer Society]] in honour of her and her husband. A year after the incident, after undergoing fertility treatments, she gave birth to a son, Ren\u00e9-Charles Dion Ang\u00e9lil, on 25 January 2001, in Florida.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070127104945/http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/01/25/dion.birth/index.html CNN]. \"Celine Dion Gives Birth to Baby Boy\". 25 January 2001. Retrieved 15 May 2007.</ref><ref>Pappas, Ben. \"Celine fights for her marriage\". ''Us''. 22 April 2002. pg 30.</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[11 September attacks]], Dion returned to the music scene, and in a televised performance sang \"[[God Bless America#Celine Dion|God Bless America]]\" at the benefit concert [[America: A Tribute to Heroes]]. Chuck Taylor of ''Billboard'' wrote, \"the performance&nbsp;... brings to mind what has made her one of the celebrated vocalists of our time: the ability to render emotion that shakes the soul. Affecting, meaningful, and filled with grace, this is a musical reflection to share with all of us still searching for ways to cope.\"<ref>Taylor, Chuck. ''C\u00e9line Dion: [[God Bless America#Celine Dion|God Bless America]]''. ''Billboard Magazine'', 6 October 2001, vol 113, issue 40; pg. 22.</ref> She performed it again in 2003 during pregame festivities for [[Super Bowl XXXVII]] in [[Qualcomm Stadium|San Diego]]. In December 2001, she published her autobiography ''My Story, My Dream'' which chronicled her rags-to-riches story.<ref name=\":2\">\"[https://www.amazon.com/Celine-Dion-My-Story-Dream/dp/0380819058 Celine Dion: ''My Story, My Dream''], Amazon.com; retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref>\n\nDion ended her three-year sabbatical from the music industry with the aptly titled album ''[[A New Day Has Come]]'', released in March 2002. The album was her most personal yet, with songs focusing on her motherhood and maturation as a woman such as \"[[A New Day Has Come (song)|A New Day Has Come]]\", and \"[[Goodbye's (The Saddest Word)]]\". She stated: \"becoming a mother makes you a grown-up.\"<ref name=\"vh1\" /> She stated, \"''A New Day Has Come'', for Rene, for me, is the baby. It has everything to do with the baby&nbsp;... That song \"A New Day Has Come\" represents very well the mood I'm feeling right now. It represents the whole album.\"<ref name=autogenerated7>Peter Nansbridge, with Alison Smith. \"Interview with Celine Dion\", ''The National'', [[CBC Television|CBC-TV]], 28 March 2002.</ref> ''A New Day Has Come'' debuted at No.&nbsp;1 in more than 17 countries, including the United Kingdom and Canada.<ref>\"[http://www.columbiarecords.com/artists.php?artistId=155143 Celine Dion profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510034950/http://www.columbiarecords.com/artists.php?artistId=155143 |date=10 May 2009 }}, columbiarecords.com; retrieved 5 December 2009.</ref><ref>[http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/D/Dion_Celine/2004/12/02/758861.html \"Celine's 'One Heart' debuts at No. 1\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120709180200/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/D/Dion_Celine/2004/12/02/758861.html |date=9 July 2012 }}; retrieved 5 December 2009.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1912466.stm Dion's CD can crash PCs], BBC.co.uk; retrieved 5 December 2009.</ref> In the United States, the album debuted at No.&nbsp;1 on the Billboard 200, with first-week sales of 527,000 copies; marking her first No.&nbsp;1 debut on the chart, as well as the highest debut sales week of her career in the US.<ref>Basham, David. (5 April 2002). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453281/20020405/dion_celine.jhtml Got Charts? Wrestling With WWF LPs; Breaking Records With Celine: A weekly tale of the tape for the statistically obsessed]; retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref> It was eventually certified 3\u00d7 Platinum in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76160/ashanti-album-single-dominate-charts|title=A New Day Has Come|date=11 April 2002|work=Billboard|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> and 6\u00d7 Platinum in Canada.<ref>[http://cria.ca/cert_db_search.php Gold and Platinum Certification], CRIA.ca; retrieved 5 December 2009. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019175407/http://cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |date=19 October 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:C\u00e9line Dion-AFR.JPG|thumb|left|Dion performing \"[[God Bless America]]\" with members of the Band of the [[US Air Force Reserve]], 2002]]\n\nWhile the album was commercially successful, critical reviews suggested that it was \"forgettable\" and the lyrics were \"lifeless\".<ref>[[Tyrangiel, Josh]]. \"Heart, No Soul\". ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''; Canadian edition. 8 April 2002. pg. 61</ref> Both Rob Sheffield of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, and Ken Tucker of ''Entertainment Weekly'', stated that Dion's music had not developed much during her break, and classed her material as trite and mediocre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rolling Stone|work=Review\u2014A New Day has come|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/_/id/175170/celinedion?pageid=rs.ArtistDiscographyMainReleases&pageregion=mainRegion|accessdate=1 November 2005|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/65TE9WfM7?url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews|archive-date=15 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,219376,00.html|title=Entertainment Weekly|work=EW.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Sal Cinquemani of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' called the album \"a lengthy collection of drippy, gooey pop fluffer-nutter\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Slant Magazine|work=Review\u2014A New Day Has Come|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=59|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021106093824/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=59|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 November 2002 |accessdate=18 July 2006}}</ref> The first single off the album, ''[[A New Day Has Come (song)|A New Day Has Come]]'' peaked at No.22 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] charts, being an airplay-only release. On the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks]], however, the song spent 21 consecutive weeks at No.&nbsp;1, breaking the record for the longest span at the top.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111013064734/http://new.music.yahoo.com/chad-kroeger/news/adult-programming-boosts-pop-vets--12179018 \"Adult Programming Boosts Pop Vets\"], yahoo.com; retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref> The previous record holders were [[Phil Collins]]' ''[[You'll Be in My Heart]]'' and Dion's own ''[[Because You Loved Me]]'', both of which lasted nineteen weeks at No.&nbsp;1. During 2002, she performed for many benefit concerts, including her second appearance on VH1 Divas Live, a concert to benefit the VH1 Save The Music Foundation, alongside [[Cher]], [[Anastacia]], [[Dixie Chicks]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Whitney Houston]], [[Cyndi Lauper]], [[Shakira]], and [[Stevie Nicks]].\n\nIn conjunction with an endorsement deal with [[Chrysler]], she released ''[[One Heart]]'' (2003), an album that represented her appreciation for life.<ref>Flick, Larry. \"One Heart\". ''Billboard'' magazine. New York: 29 March 2003. Vol.115, Iss. 13; pg. 30, 1 pg</ref> The album largely consisted of pop and dance music\u2014a deviation from the soaring, melodramatic ballads, for which she had been known. Although the album achieved moderate success, ''One Heart'' was met with mixed criticism, and words such as \"predictable\" and \"banal\" appeared even in the most lenient reviews.<ref name=One>{{cite web|title=Allmusic|work=Review\u2014One Heart|url= {{Allmusic|class=album|id=r633121|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=17 July 2006}}</ref><ref>Durchholz, Daniel. ''One Heart:C\u00e9line's a Diva Who Still Goes On and On''. ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'', 24 April 2003. pg. F3</ref> A cover of the 1989 Cyndi Lauper hit \"[[I Drove All Night#C\u00e9line Dion version|I Drove All Night]]\", released to launch her advertising campaign with [[Chrysler]],<ref>Stein, Jason. \"Celine Dion sings flat for Chrysler\". ''Automotive News''. 24 November 2003. Volume 78.</ref> incorporated elements of dance-pop and rock and roll. The advertising deal was met with criticism, with some stating that Dion was trying to cater to her sponsors.<ref>Murray, Sonia. ''C\u00e9line Dion's latest takes easy, well-worn route''. ''The Atlanta Journal\u2013Constitution'', 25 March 2003, pg. C1.</ref><ref>Kiley, David. (8 June 2003) \"[http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/advertising/adtrack/2003-06-08-dion_x.htm Chrysler bets big on Dion's auto endorsement deal]\", ''[[USA Today]]''; retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref>\n\nAfter ''One Heart'', she released her next English-language studio album, ''[[Miracle (Celine Dion album)|Miracle]]'' (2004). ''Miracle'' was a multimedia project conceived by Dion and Australian photographer [[Anne Geddes]] and had a theme centring on babies and motherhood. The album was filled with lullabies and other songs of maternal love and inspiration, including covers of [[Louis Armstrong]]'s \"[[What a Wonderful World]]\" and [[John Lennon]]'s \"[[Beautiful Boy (Darling Boy)#C\u00e9line Dion version|Beautiful Boy]]\". The reviews for ''Miracle'' were mixed.<ref name=celebr>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r709313|pure_url=yes}} Miracle: A Celebration of New Life]. Allmusic.com; retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref> Stephen Thomas Erlewine of Allmusic.com gave the album three of out five stars, stating, \"The worst you can say about the record is that there are no surprises, but the audience for this record doesn't want surprises; they want comfort, whether it arrives in polished music or artsy photos of newborns, and Miracle provides both, which makes it appealing for those expectant or new mothers in Dion's audience.\"<ref name=\"celebr\"/> [[Chuck Taylor (Billboard writer and editor)|Chuck Taylor]] of ''Billboard'' magazine wrote that the single \"Beautiful Boy\" was \"an unexpected gem\" and called Dion \"a timeless, enormously versatile artist\",<ref>Taylor, Chuck. ''C\u00e9line Dion: \"Beautiful Boy\"''. ''Billboard''. New York: 16 October 2004. Vol.116, Iss. 42; pg. 33.</ref> Chuck Arnold of ''People'' Magazine, however, labelled the album as excessively sentimental,<ref>Arnold, Chuck. \"Review: Celine Dion, Miracle\". ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', 22 November 2004. pg, 48.</ref> while Nancy Miller of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' opined that \"the whole earth-mama act is just opportunism, reborn\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Entertainment Weekly|work=Review: Miracle|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/review/music/0,6115,724253_4_0_,00.html|accessdate=30 November 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070522061729/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C724253%2C00.html|archivedate=22 May 2007}}</ref> ''Miracle'' debuted at No.&nbsp;4 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and No.&nbsp;1 in Canada and was eventually certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120524143006/http://riaa.org/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH GOLD & PLATINUM]; retrieved 5 December 2009.</ref>\n\nThe francophone album ''[[1 fille & 4 types]]'' (''1 Girl & 4 Guys''), released in October 2003, fared better than her previous two releases and showed her trying to distance herself from the \"diva\" image. She recruited [[Jean-Jacques Goldman]], [[Gildas Arzel]], Eric Benzi, and Jacques Veneruso, with whom she had previously worked on two of her best-selling French albums ''[[S'il suffisait d'aimer]]'' and ''[[D'eux]]''. Labeled \"the album of pleasure\" by Dion herself, the album cover showed her in a simple and relaxed manner, contrary to the choreographed poses usually found on her album covers. The album achieved widespread commercial success in France, Canada, and Belgium where it reached No.&nbsp;1. In France, the album debuted at No.&nbsp;1 and was later certified 2\u00d7 platinum after selling over 700,000 copies. Critic Stephen Erlewine of ''[[AllMusic]]'' wrote that Dion's vocals were \"back at top of their game\" and that she was \"getting back to pop basics and performing at a level unheard in a while\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Allmusic|work=Review\u20141 Fille & 4 Types|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r666176|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=20 November 2005}}</ref>\n\nThough her albums were commercially successful, they did not achieve the sales or the reception of her previous works. Her songs received less airplay as radio became less embracing of balladeers like Dion, Carey, and Houston, and was focused on more up-tempo, [[Urban contemporary|Urban]]/[[Hip hop music|Hip-hop]] songs.<ref>Gardner, Elysa. [https://www.usatoday.com/life/dcovfri.htm Mariah Carey, 'standing again']. ''[[USA Today]]'', 28 November 2002; retrieved 19 August 2005.</ref> By 2004, Dion had accumulated sales of more than 175 million albums worldwide and received the Chopard Diamond Award from the World Music Awards for her achievements. According to the official World Music Awards website, the award is rare; it is \"not presented every year\" and an artist can be presented with the award only for selling \"over 100 million albums during their career\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldmusicawards.com/index2.html|title=Diamond Award|publisher=World Music Awards|year=2010|accessdate=3 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127183948/http://www.worldmusicawards.com/index2.html|archivedate=27 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2003\u20132007: ''A New Day...''===\nIn early 2002, Dion announced a three-year, 600-show contract to appear five nights a week in an entertainment extravaganza, ''[[A New Day...]]'', at [[The Colosseum at Caesars Palace]], Las Vegas.<ref name=Lavid>{{cite journal|last=Helligar|first=Jeremy|title=C\u00e9line Dion livin' la vida Vegas!|newspaper=Us|date=31 March 2003|page=56}}</ref> This move was generally seen as risky, but journalist Miriam Nunzio wrote that it was \"one of the smartest business decisions in years by any major recording artist\".<ref>Di Nunzio, Miriam (20 March 2009)[https://web.archive.org/web/20121104190437/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1567185.html 'A New Day': Vegas gamble pays off for Celine Dion], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''; retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref> Dion conceived the show after seeing ''[[O (Cirque du Soleil)|O]]'' by [[Franco Dragone]] during her break from recording, and it premiered on 25 March 2003, in a 4,000-seat arena specifically designed for her show and modelled after the Roman Colosseum.<ref name=\"Lavid\"/> Many stars attended the opening night including [[Dick Clark]], [[Alan Thicke]], [[Kathy Griffin]], [[Lance Bass]], and [[Justin Timberlake]], who hosted the television special.<ref>Gardner, Elysa. (26 March 2003) [https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2003-03-24-dion-show_x.htm \"Celine Dion's 'New Day' dawns with a TV preview\"]. ''[[USA Today]]''; retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref> The show, directed by Dragone and choreographed by the renowned [[Mia Michaels]], was a combination of dance, music, and visual effects. It included Dion performing her biggest hits against an array of dancers and special effects. Reviewer Mike Weatherford felt that, at first, Dion was not as relaxed as she should be, and at times, it was hard to find the singer among the excessive stage ornamentation and dancers. However, he noted that the show had become more enjoyable over the course of its run, because of her improved stage-presence and simplified costumes.<ref name=\"autogenerated19\" />\n\nThe show was well-received by audiences, despite the complaints of expensive tickets{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}; it routinely sold out until its end in late 2007.<ref>Ryzik, Melena (17 December 2007) \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/17/arts/17iht-17celi.8775167.html Celine Dion, she went on and on]\". ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref> Ticket prices averaged $135.33.<ref>Hau, Louis (19 September 2007). \"[https://www.forbes.com/2007/09/19/music-madonna-rolling_stones-biz-media-cx_lh_0919musicians.html The Top-Earning Musicians]. ''[[Forbes]]''. Retrieved 14 October 2009.</ref> According to ''[[Pollstar]]'', Dion sold 322,000 tickets and grossed US$43.9&nbsp;million in the first half of 2005, and by July 2005, she had sold out 315 out of 384 shows.<ref>{{cite news | title= Dion extends long Las Vegas stint| date= 19 September 2004 |publisher=BBC | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3670760.stm | accessdate=2 January 2010}}</ref> By the end of 2005, she grossed more than US$76&nbsp;million, placing sixth on ''Billboard's Money Makers list for 2005''.<ref>{{cite web | title=Billboard.com | work=U2 Tops Billboard's Money Makers Chart| url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/59982/u2-tops-billboards-money-makers-chart| accessdate=25 January 2006}}</ref> ''A New Day...'' was the 6th biggest-selling tour in the US in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=YouTube|work=C\u00e9line Dion|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaAi8V3k8YE|accessdate=20 October 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726193237/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaAi8V3k8YE|archivedate=26 July 2013}}</ref> Because of the show's success, her contract was extended into 2007 for an undisclosed sum. On 5 January 2007, it was announced that the show would end on 15 December 2007, with tickets for the period after October 2007 having gone on sale from 1 March.<ref>{{cite news|title=C\u00e9line Dion is leaving Las Vegas|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6233473.stm|accessdate=5 January 2007|work=BBC News}}</ref> According to ''Billboard'', A New Day... is the most successful residency of all time, grossing over US$385 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|385|r=2|2007}}}} million in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars){{inflation-fn|US}} and drawing nearly three million people to 717 shows.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KhQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38#v=onepage Review: A New Day]; accessed 27 June 2017.</ref> The ''[[Live in Las Vegas: A New Day...]]'' DVD was released on 10 December 2007, in Europe and the following day in North America.<ref>{{cite web| title= Celine Dion debuts new single, \"Taking Chances\"... new Album and Worldwide tour, to come!| date=12 September 2007|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca-fr/node/68191|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204030214/http://www.celinedion.com/ca-fr/node/68191|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 December 2012|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher=Sony Music Entertainment Canada Inc.}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132010: ''D'elles'', ''Taking Chances'' and Taking Chances Tour===\nOn 21 May 2007, Dion released the French-language album ''[[D'elles]]'' ''(About Them)'', which debuted at the top of the Canadian album charts, selling 72,200 copies in its first week. It marked her tenth No. 1 album in the SoundScan era, and her eighth to debut at the top position. In Canada, the album has been certified 2\u00d7 platinum, and within the first month had already shipped half a million units worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | work=Celinedion.com|title=Celine's 'D'elles' Debuted #1 on the Charts and Certified 2X Platinum in Canada!|url=http://www.celinedion.com/node/65791|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709111755/http://www.celinedion.com/node/65791|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 July 2012|date=1 June 2007|accessdate=1 June 2007}}</ref> ''D'Elles'' also reached No. 1 in France and Belgium. The first single \"[[Et s'il n'en restait qu'une (je serais celle-l\u00e0)]]\" (meaning \"And If There Was Only One Woman Left (I Would Be That One)\") debuted at the top of the French singles chart a month earlier. Later that same year, she released the English album ''[[Taking Chances]]'' on 12 November in Europe, and 13 November in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/node/67831|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712115213/http://www.celinedion.com/node/67831|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 July 2012|title='Taking Chances' \u2013 Celine's New English Album|work=Celinedion.com|date=24 August 2007|accessdate=9 May 2007}}</ref> Her first English studio album since 2003's ''One Heart'', it featured pop, R&B, and rock inspired music.<ref>Eva Simpson & Caroline Hedley. \"3AM: Celine Dion\", ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', 30 July 2007. pg 17.</ref> For this album, she collaborated with [[John Shanks]] and ex-[[Evanescence]] guitarist [[Ben Moody]], as well as [[Kristian Lundin]], [[Peer \u00c5str\u00f6m]], [[Linda Perry]], Japanese singer [[Yuna Ito]], and R&B singer-songwriter [[Ne-Yo]].<ref>Johnson, Kevin C. \"Ne-Yo Rides His R&B Vision to the Top\", ''Saint Louis Post-Dispatch''. 21 June 2007. pg. 5.</ref><ref>Taylor, Chuck. \"[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1049364/celine-ready-to-take-chances-on-new-album Celine Ready To Take 'Chances' On New Album]\". ''Billboard''. 11 September 2007. Retrieved 13 September 2007.</ref> Dion stated, \"I think this album represents a positive evolution in my career&nbsp;... I'm feeling strong, maybe a little gutsier than in the past, and just as passionate about music and life as I ever was.\"<ref>\"[http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/2007-08-09-coming-attractions_n.htm Coming attractions: Dion channels cool, fiesty (sic) 'Woman']\". ''[[USA Today]]''. 13 September 2007.</ref> She launched her year-long worldwide [[Taking Chances Tour]] on 14 February 2008, in South Africa, performing 132 dates in stadiums and arenas across five continents.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070511234934/http://www.celinedion.com/celinedion/english/whatsgoinon_tourdates.cgi \"Concert Dates\"]. celinedion.com. Retrieved 7 November 2007.</ref>\n\nThe Taking Chances Tour was a great success in the United States, reaching the No.&nbsp;1 spot on the ''Billboard'' Boxscore, having sold out every concert in the US and Canada. In addition, she appeared on [[Idol Gives Back]] for a second year in a row. Dion was nominated for six [[Juno Awards]] in 2008, adding to her 53 previous nominations (an all-time record). Her nominations included Artist of the Year, Pop Album of the Year (for ''Taking Chances''), Francophone Album of the Year (for ''D'elles'') and Album of the Year (for both ''Taking Chances'' and ''D'elles'').<ref>[http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/theampersand/archive/2008/02/05/lavigne-dion-feist-oh-my.aspx Juno Awards] {{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}. ''[[National Post]]''. Retrieved 3 April 2008.</ref> The following year, she was nominated for 3 Juno Awards including the Fan Choice Award, Song of the Year (for ''Taking Chances''), and Music DVD of the Year (for ''Live in Las Vegas&nbsp;\u2014 A New Day...'')<ref>Collins, Leah (3 February 2009) [http://www2.canada.com/sports/football/nickelback+leads+juno+nominations/1248346/story.html?id=1248346 \"Nickelback leads Juno nominations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914191332/http://www2.canada.com/sports/football/nickelback+leads+juno+nominations/1248346/story.html?id=1248346 |date=14 September 2011 }}\". Canada.com; retrieved 15 October 2009.</ref>\n\nOn 22 August 2008, Dion presented a free outdoor concert, mostly in French, on the [[Plains of Abraham]], in [[Qu\u00e9bec City]], Canada, for the [[400th anniversary of Quebec City|400th anniversary of Qu\u00e9bec City]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Richer, Jocelyne|title=C\u00e9line Dion \u00e0 Qu\u00e9bec vendredi le 400e promet un spectacle m\u00e9morable|publisher=Yahoo! news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/arts/spectacles-et-theatre/200809/08/01-664111-quebec-se-prepare-a-accueillir-celine-dion.php|year=2008|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> The celebration gathered approximately 490,000 people. The concert, called ''[[C\u00e9line sur les Plaines]]'', was released on DVD on 11 November 2008, in Qu\u00e9bec and was released on 20 May 2009, in France.<ref>[http://tvanouvelles.ca/lcn/artsetspectacles/general/archives/2008/08/20080823-071822.html C\u00e9line sur les Plaines: Un moment rempli d'\u00e9motions], tvanouvelles.ca, 23 August 2008.</ref> Late October 2008 saw the worldwide release of a comprehensive English-language greatest hits album, ''[[My Love: Essential Collection]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/node/80632|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407020832/http://www.celinedion.com/node/80632|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 April 2012|title=New Greatest Hits Album: TeamCeline Exclusive Sneak Peek!|work=Celinedion.com|accessdate=27 August 2008|date=26 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Dion was named the 20th best-selling artist of the decade and the second-best-selling female artist of the decade in the United States, selling an estimated 17.57&nbsp;million copies of her albums there since 2000.<ref>(29 May 2009) \"[http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/chart-watch-extra-the-top-20-album-sellers-of-the-2000s.html Chart Watch Extra: The Top 20 Album Sellers Of The 2000s] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115034358/http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/chart-watch-extra-the-top-20-album-sellers-of-the-2000s.html |date=15 January 2012 }}\". music.yahoo.com. Retrieved 15 October 2009.</ref> In June 2009, ''Forbes'' reported that she earned $100&nbsp;million during 2008. In December 2009, Pollstar announced that she was the best-selling solo touring act of the decade and the second-best-selling touring act of the decade, behind only the [[Dave Matthews Band]].<ref name=\"chicagotribune.com\">[http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/chi-sc-ent-1221-decade-touringdec21,0,3057461.story Dave Matthews Band rocks to the top in concert revenue] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012132154/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/chi-sc-ent-1221-decade-touringdec21,0,3057461.story |date=12 October 2011 }} ''Chicago Tribune''. Retrieved 20 December 2009.</ref> she grossed $522.2&nbsp;million during the decade, a large portion of that sum coming from her five-year residency at [[Caesars Palace]].<ref name=\"chicagotribune.com\"/>\n\nOn 17 February 2010, Dion released into theatres a documentary film about her ''Taking Chances Tour'', titled, ''[[Celine: Through the Eyes of the World]]''.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\">- (3 December 2009) \"[https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2009-12-03-celine03_ST_N.htm/ 'Eyes of the World': Part Dion concert film, part family album]\". usatoday.com; retrieved 4 December 2009.</ref> The documentary shows behind-the-scenes footage of her both onstage and offstage, along with footage of her with her family as they travelled the world with her. The distributor is the [[Sony Pictures Entertainment|Sony Pictures]] subsidiary, [[Hot Ticket]].<ref name=\"usatoday.com\"/> The film was later released on Blu-ray and DVD on 4 May 2010, along with the CD/DVD, ''[[Taking Chances World Tour: The Concert]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/celine-through-the-eyes-of-the-world-an-expanded-dvd-edition-of-the-acclaimed-documentary--taking-chances-world-tour-the-concert-a-new-live-dvdcd-available-tuesday-may-4-88804797.html|title=Celine: Through the Eyes of the World, an Expanded DVD Edition of the Acclaimed Documentary & Taking Chances World Tour: The Concert, a New Live DVD/CD, Available Tuesday, May 4|date=22 March 2010|publisher=Prnewswire.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonymusicdigital.com/celine-dion/pages/5472878/|title=Celine Dion store|publisher=Sonymusicdigital.com|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308074359/http://www.sonymusicdigital.com/celine-dion/pages/5472878/|archivedate=8 March 2011}}</ref> At the [[2010 Grammy Awards|52nd Grammy Awards]] in February 2010, Dion joined [[Carrie Underwood]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], [[Jennifer Hudson]], and [[Smokey Robinson]] to perform the song \"[[Earth Song]]\" during the 3-D [[Michael Jackson]] tribute.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1630895/michael-jackson-grammy-tribute-focuses-on-his-love-planet.jhtml|title=Michael Jackson 'Earth Song' Grammy Tribute Focuses On His Love Of The Planet|publisher=MTV|date=31 January 2010|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:CelineDion concert.jpg|thumb|left|C\u00e9line Dion on stage performing \"[[Eyes on Me (Celine Dion song)|Eyes on Me]]\" during her [[Taking Chances Tour]] in [[Montr\u00e9al]], Canada in August 2008]]\nIn January 2010, ''The [[Los Angeles Times]]'' presented its annual list of the top ten largest earners of the year, revealing that Dion took the top spot for the entire decade, with [[United States dollar|$US]]747.9&nbsp;million in total revenue from 2000\u20132009.<ref name=\"latimesblogs.latimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/01/celine-dion-reaches-peak-of-the-decades-ultimate-top-10.html|title=Celine Dion reaches peak of the decade's Ultimate Top 10|publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com|date=18 January 2010}}</ref> The largest haul came from ticket sales, totalling $522.2&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"latimesblogs.latimes.com\"/> Additionally, she was named \"Artist of the Decade\" in her native Canadian province of Qu\u00e9bec, announced by the [[Montr\u00e9al]]-based newspaper, ''Le Journal de Qu\u00e9bec'' in 2009 December.<ref name=\"lejournaldequebec.canoe.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://lejournaldequebec.canoe.ca/journaldequebec/artsetspectacles/encoreplus/archives/2009/12/20091230-203458.html|title=Les artistes qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois de la d\u00e9cennie|work=Le Journal de Qu\u00e9bec|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> A public [[online survey]] asked responders to vote for whom they believe deserved the above-mentioned accolade.<ref name=\"lejournaldequebec.canoe.ca\"/>\n\nFurthermore, in a May 2010 [[Harris Poll]], Dion was named the most popular musician in the United States, ahead of [[U2]], [[Elvis Presley]], and [[The Beatles]] while factoring in gender, political affiliations, geographic region of residence, and income.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/aw/content_display/news/agency/e3i0b2233969ec82f2cdc3404f3d0002bc8 |title=Celine Dion Is Americans' Musical Fave |publisher=AdWeek |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=16 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510024851/http://www.adweek.com/aw/content_display/news/agency/e3i0b2233969ec82f2cdc3404f3d0002bc8 |archivedate=10 May 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Specifically, she was the most popular musician in the female demographic, as well as among all Democrats, those who live in the eastern United States and southern United States, and those who have incomes between US$35k and US$74.9k.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsblaze.com/entertainment/music/celine-dion-edges-out-u2-as-americas-favorite-singer-musician_13637/|title=Celine Dion is America's Favorite Singer/Musician Followed by U2|publisher=newsblaze.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.finchannel.com/news_flash/CityLife/63318_Harris_Poll%3A_Celine_Dion_is_America's_Favorite_Singer%10Musician_Followed_by_U2/ Harris Poll: Celine Dion is America's Favorite Singer/Musician Followed by U2]. ''The Financial''. Retrieved 7 December 2010  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510132022/http://www.finchannel.com/news_flash/CityLife/63318_Harris_Poll%3A_Celine_Dion_is_America%27s_Favorite_Singer%10Musician_Followed_by_U2/ |date=10 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, she released the single \"[[Voler]]\", a duet with French singer [[Michel Sardou]]. The song was later included on Sardou's album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canoe.com/divertissement/musique/nouvelles/2010/09/22/15440861-ca.html|title=VOLER Michel Sardou en duo avec C\u00e9line Dion|publisher=Canoe.com|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118091000/http://www.canoe.com/divertissement/musique/nouvelles/2010/09/22/15440861-ca.html|archivedate=18 January 2012}}</ref> In addition, it was announced in October 2010 that Dion wrote and composed a new song for Canadian singer, [[Marc Dupr\u00e9]] entitled \"Entre deux mondes\".<ref>[http://www.matin.qc.ca/article_culture.php?id=60358&section=musique Marc Dupre: un nouvel extrait compose par Celine Dion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313143758/http://www.matin.qc.ca/article_culture.php?id=60358&section=musique |date=13 March 2012 }} ''Branchez-vous!''. Retrieved 10 October 2010.</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132014: ''Celine'', ''Sans attendre'' and ''Loved Me Back to Life''===\nIn an interview with ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine published in February 2010, Dion announced that she would be returning to Caesars Palace in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] for ''[[Celine (concert residency)|Celine]]'', a three-year residency for seventy shows a year, beginning 15 March 2011.<ref name=\"people1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20343176,00.html|title=Celine Dion Confirms Her Return to Vegas Stage|work=PEOPLE.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> She stated that the show will feature, \"all the songs from my repertoire that people want to hear\" and will contain a selection of music from classic Hollywood films.<ref name=\"people1\"/> To promote her return to Las Vegas, Dion made an appearance on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' on 21 February, during the show's final season, marking her record twenty-seventh appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/Celine-Dions-Oprah-Show-Retrospective |title=Celine Dion Retrospective \u2013 1996 |publisher=Oprah.com |date=21 February 2011 |accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/feb/21/celine-dion-discusses-las-vegas-show-gives-away-ti/|title=Celine Dion discusses Las Vegas show, gives away tickets on 'Oprah'|work=LasVegasSun.com|date=21 February 2011}}</ref>   In 2018, ''Billboard'' stated her residency ''Celine'' is the second most successful residency of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8491648/highest-grossing-las-vegas-residencies|title=Top 10 Highest Grossing Las Vegas Residencies Of All Time: Celine Dion, Britney Spears, Elton John and More|website=Billboard|accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor a record sixth time, she performed at the [[83rd Academy Awards]], where she sang the song \"Smile\", as part of the ceremony's \"In Memoriam\" segment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.eonline.com/news/226282/we-know-celine-dion-s-post-baby-plans-hint-think-oscar|title=We Know C\u00e9line Dion's Post-Baby Plans (Hint: Think Oscar!)|date=15 February 2011|work=E! Online|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> On 4 September, she appeared on the 2011 MDA Labor Telethon Event and presented a prerecorded performance of \"[[Open Arms (Journey song)|Open Arms]]\" from her new Las Vegas show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/news/celine-mda-labor-day-telethon-tonight|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407021613/http://www.celinedion.com/news/celine-mda-labor-day-telethon-tonight|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 April 2012|title=Celine on MDA Labor Day Telethon Tonight|work=Celinedion.com|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref> On 1 October 2011, the OWN Network premiered a documentary on Dion's life, detailing the months before, during and after her pregnancy, to the makings of her new Las Vegas Show, called, \"Celine: 3 Boys and a New Show\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/news/%E2%80%98celine-3-boys-and-new-show%E2%80%99-own-weekend |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002171611/http://www.celinedion.com/news/%E2%80%98celine-3-boys-and-new-show%E2%80%99-own-weekend|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title='Celine: 3 Boys and a New Show' On OWN This Weekend!|work=Celinedion.com|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref> The documentary became the second highest rated show on TV OWN Canada. In October, FlightNetwork.com conducted a poll asking 780 participants which celebrity they would most like to sit next to on an airplane. Dion was the top favourite, with 23.7% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/news/who-your-dream-celebrity-seat-mate |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018104813/http://www.celinedion.com/news/who-your-dream-celebrity-seat-mate |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 October 2011 |title=Who Is Your Dream Celebrity Seat-Mate? &#124; The Official Celine Dion Site |work=Celinedion.com |accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref> Also, in September, she released the 14th perfume from her [[Celine Dion Parfums]] Collection, called \"Signature\".<ref name=\"celinedion1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/news/signature-%E2%80%93-celine%E2%80%99s-new-fragrance-coming-soon-boutique |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104093621/http://www.celinedion.com/news/signature-%E2%80%93-celine%E2%80%99s-new-fragrance-coming-soon-boutique |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 January 2012 |title=Signature \u2013 Celine's New Fragrance, Coming Soon To The Boutique &#124; The Official Celine Dion Site |work=Celinedion.com|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref> On 15 September, she made an appearance at the [[Concerto: One Night in Central Park|free concert]] of world-famous tenor, [[Andrea Bocelli]], in Central Park in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/news/celine-appear-andrea-bocelli%E2%80%99s-concert-central-park |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407021737/http://www.celinedion.com/news/celine-appear-andrea-bocelli%E2%80%99s-concert-central-park |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 April 2012 |title=Celine To Appear At Andrea Bocelli's Concert in Central Park &#124; The Official Celine Dion Site |work=Celinedion.com|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref> In 2012, she performed at the 16th Jazz and Blues Festival in [[Jamaica]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jayblessed.com/2012/01/29/videos-celine-dion-performing-live-at-2012-jamaica-jazz-and-blues/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203003037/http://www.jayblessed.com/2012/01/29/videos-celine-dion-performing-live-at-2012-jamaica-jazz-and-blues|url-status=dead |archive-date=3 February 2012|title=VIDEOS: Celine Dion performing LIVE at 2012 Jamaica Jazz and Blues!|publisher=Jayblessed.com|accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Sony Music Entertainment released ''[[The Best of Celine Dion & David Foster]]'' in Asia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.5music.com.tw/cdList-c.asp?cdno=433475678927|title=The Best of Celine Dion & David Foster|language=Chinese|publisher=Five Music|accessdate=19 October 2012}}</ref> She began recording songs for her next English and French albums during April and May 2012.<ref name=cd1>{{cite web|title=Celine's New Albums|publisher=celinedion.com|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/celine%E2%80%99s-new-albums|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120803234854/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/celine%E2%80%99s-new-albums|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 August 2012|date=7 June 2012|accessdate=21 September 2012}}</ref> The French-language album, ''[[Sans attendre]]'' was released on 2 November 2012, and was a smash success in all French-speaking territories, especially in France where it achieved diamond status.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Sans attendre\" \u2013 A Big Day For Germany, Switzerland and Belgium|publisher=celinedion.com|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/sans-attendre%E2%80%99-%E2%80%93-big-day-germany-switzerland-and-belgium|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104190003/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/sans-attendre%E2%80%99-%E2%80%93-big-day-germany-switzerland-and-belgium |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2012 |date=2 November 2012 |accessdate=2 November 2012}}</ref> The English-language album was postponed to 1 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Release Dates For 'Loved Me Back To Life' |publisher=celinedion.com |url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/release-dates-%E2%80%98loved-me-back-life%E2%80%99 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130907153051/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/release-dates-%E2%80%98loved-me-back-life%E2%80%99 |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 September 2013 |date=4 September 2013 |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> Titled ''[[Loved Me Back to Life]]'', it included collaborations with an exceptional team of songwriters and producers, including duets with [[Ne-Yo]] and [[Stevie Wonder]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion: Loved Me Back to Life |publisher=celinedion.com |url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/music/loved-me-back-life |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908090028/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/music/loved-me-back-life |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 September 2013 |date=4 September 2013 |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> The lead single, \"[[Loved Me Back to Life (song)|Loved Me Back to Life]]\" was released on 3 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5679741/celine-dion-talks-loved-me-back-to-life-single-album-exclusive|title=Celine Dion Talks 'Loved Me Back to Life' Single, Album (Exclusive)|date=29 August 2013|accessdate=29 August 2013|work=Billboard}}</ref> Dion embarked on the [[Sans attendre Tour]] in November 2013 and performed in Belgium and France.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Returns to Europe for 7 Exceptional shows|publisher=celinedion.com|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/press/celine-dion-returns-europe-7-exceptional-shows|accessdate=23 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426100121/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/press/celine-dion-returns-europe-7-exceptional-shows|archivedate=26 April 2013}}</ref> \"[[Breakaway (Celine Dion song)|Breakaway]]\", \"[[Incredible (Celine Dion and Ne-Yo song)|Incredible]]\" and \"[[Water and a Flame#Celine Dion version|Water and a Flame]]\" were chosen as next singles.<ref>{{cite web|title='Loved Me Back To Life' Certified Gold and a New Single in the UK!|publisher=celinedion.com|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/%E2%80%98loved-me-back-life%E2%80%99-certified-gold-and-new-single-uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203000454/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/%E2%80%98loved-me-back-life%E2%80%99-certified-gold-and-new-single-uk|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 December 2013|date=2 December 2013|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NeYoCompound/status/398575180793933824|title=\"Incredible\" the next single from @celinedion|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref> The music video for \"Incredible\" was uploaded onto her official [[Vevo]] channel in early June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=C\u00e9line Dion duet with Ne-Yo \u2013 Incredible |publisher=Vevo|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QvO5z5tx4ZA|date=5 June 2014|accessdate=5 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 May 2014, Dion released a three-disc set (2CD/DVD and 2CD/Blu-ray) titled ''[[C\u00e9line une seule fois / Live 2013]]'', which reached top ten on the album charts in France, Canada and Belgium Wallonia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion releases 'C\u00e9line une seule fois / Live 2013' May 19th|publisher=celinedion.com|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/press/celine-dion-releases-%E2%80%98c%C3%A9line-une-seule-foislive-2013%E2%80%99-may-19th|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502211646/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/press/celine-dion-releases-%E2%80%98c%C3%A9line-une-seule-foislive-2013%E2%80%99-may-19th|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 May 2014|date=22 April 2014|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=CelineDion.com is not an independent source |date=May 2014}}\n\n===2014\u2013present: Husband's death, ''Encore un soir'' and ''Courage''===\nOn 13 August 2014, Dion announced the indefinite postponement of all her show business activities, including her concert residency at Caesars Palace in Las Vegas, and the cancellation of her [[Asia Tour]], because of the worsening of her husband's health after he underwent the removal of a cancerous tumor in December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/celine-dion-cancels-tour-husband-rene-angelils-illness/story?id=24959133 |title=Celine Dion Cancels Tour Because of Husband Rene Angelil's Illness |author=Lesley Messer |date=13 August 2014|work=ABC News |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Celine Dion Puts Career on Hold 'Indefinitely' to Deal With Husband's Health | url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6214488/celine-dion-career-on-hold-health-issues | work = Billboard| date = 13 August 2014 | accessdate = 14 August 2014 | author = Joe Lynch }}</ref> However, on 20 March 2015, she announced that she would be returning to [[The Colosseum at Caesars Palace]] in late August 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/article/celine-dion-returns-las-vegas-residency|title=C\u00e9line Dion Will Return to Las Vegas Stage|author=Jennifer Garcia|date=20 March 2015|work=People.com|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref> On 14 January 2016, she cancelled the rest of the January performances due to her husband's and her brother's death from cancer.<ref name=\"axs.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.axs.com/events/274757/celine-dion-tickets?skin=colosseum |title=Celine Dion |author=axs.com |date=14 January 2016 |work=axs.com |accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> Dion resumed the residency on 23 February to a sold-out crowd and rave reviews.\n\nIn October 2015, Dion announced on social media that she had begun working on a new French album, posting a photo by the side of Algerian singer [[Zaho]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Begins Work On New French Language Album|publisher=idolator.com|url=http://www.idolator.com/7612442/celine-dion-new-french-album-2016-zaho|date=22 October 2015|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref> Dion's French single, \"[[Encore un soir]]\", was released on 24 May 2016. On 20 May, she released a cover of [[Queen (band)|Queen]]'s song \"[[The Show Must Go On (Queen song)#Celine Dion version|The Show Must Go On]]\", featuring [[Lindsey Stirling]] on violin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.celinedion.com/celine-releases-show-must-go-onfeaturing-linsdey-stirling/awards|title=Celine releases \"The Show Must Go On\" featuring Lindsey Stirling|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=21 May 2016|publisher=celinedion.com}}{{dead link|date=April 2017}}</ref> She performed \"The Show Must Go On\" at the [[2016 Billboard Music Awards|2016 ''Billboard'' Music Awards]] on 22 May, and received the [[Billboard Icon Award|''Billboard'' Icon Award]] (presented to her by her son, Ren\u00e9-Charles Ang\u00e9lil) in recognition of her career spanning over three decades.<ref name=\"Celine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7356823/celine-dion-icon-award-perform-2016-billboard-music-awards|title=Celine Dion to Receive ICON Award|work=Billboard|date=4 May 2016|accessdate=1 June 2016|author=Billboard Staff}}</ref>\n\nThe singer's new French album, ''[[Encore un soir (album)|Encore un soir]]'', was released on 26 August 2016. It features fifteen tracks performed in French and, according to the singer, has a personal choice of the songs \u2013 more uplifting lyrics were chosen.<ref name=\"Encore une soir\">{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/music/celine-dions-new-album-out-aug-26|title=C\u00e9line Dion's new album out Aug. 26|work=Montreal Gazette|date=17 July 2016|accessdate=19 July 2016|author=Montreal Gazette}}</ref> ''Encore un soir'' topped the charts in France, Canada, Belgium and Switzerland, and was certified Diamond in France, 2\u00d7 Platinum in Canada and Platinum in Belgium and Switzerland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=C%E9line+Dion&titel=Encore+un+soir&cat=a|title=Lescharts.com \u2013 C\u00e9line Dion \u2013 Encore un soir|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snepmusique.com/les-disques-dor/?awards_cat=65&awards_artist=C%C3%A9line+Dion&awards_title=Encore+un+soir|title=Albums \u2013 SNEP|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> It has sold over 1.5 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=C\u00e9line Dion pr\u00e9sente un nouvel extrait de son album \"Encore un soir\"|publisher=frequence-plaisir.com|url=http://frequence-plaisir.com/news/celine-dion-presente-un-nouvel-extrait-de-son-album-encore-un-soir-204|date=13 February 2017|accessdate=10 August 2017|language=French}}</ref> In [[Summer Tour 2016|2016]] and [[Celine Dion Live 2017|2017]], Dion toured Europe and Canada with two sold-out concert tours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore |title=Billboard Boxscore :: Current Scores |date=19 July 2016|work=Billboard |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722124529/http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore |archivedate=22 July 2016|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore |title=Billboard Boxscore :: Current Scores |date=6 September 2016|work=Billboard |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908000224/http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore |archivedate=8 September 2016 |accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|title=Billboard Boxscore :: Current Scores|date=5 July 2017|work=Billboard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705175126/http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|archivedate=5 July 2017|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|title=Billboard Boxscore :: Current Scores|date=26 July 2017|work=Billboard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725220855/http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|archivedate=25 July 2017|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|title=Billboard Boxscore :: Current Scores|date=8 August 2017|work=Billboard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808080135/http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|archivedate=8 August 2017|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> On 9 September 2016, she released \"[[Recovering]]\", a song written for her by [[Pink (singer)|Pink]] after Dion's husband [[Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil]] died in January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://etcanada.com/photos/189154/the-25-best-songs-of-2016/#image-189176|title=The 25 best Songs of 2016|work=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada]]|author=Graeme O'Neil|date=19 December 2016|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> Dion also recorded \"[[How Does a Moment Last Forever]]\" for the ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 soundtrack)|Beauty and the Beast: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'', released in March 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/music/celine-dion-almost-turned-down-beauty-and-the-beast-song_1983313.html|title=Celine Dion almost turned down 'Beauty and the Beast' song|date=4 March 2017|work=Zee News|accessdate=10 August 2017|language=en}}</ref> Her compilation, ''[[Un peu de nous]]'' topped the chart in France in July and August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snepmusique.com/tops-semaine/top-album-megafusion/?ye=2017&we=31|title=Le Top de la semaine : Top Albums \u2013 SNEP|publisher=Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 May 2018, she released the single \"[[Ashes (Celine Dion song)|Ashes]]\" from the film ''[[Deadpool 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Debuts Epic New Single & Video 'Ashes' For 'Deadpool 2': Watch|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8451472/celine-dion-ashes-video-deadpool-2|author=Mackenzie Cummings-Grady|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=3 May 2018|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref> The remix version of the song topped the US [[Dance Club Songs]] chart in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Smolders at No. 1 on Dance Club Songs Chart With 'Ashes'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8466245/celine-dion-ashes-dance-club-songs-chart-number-1|author=Gordon Murray|work=Billboard|date=19 July 2018|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> From June to August 2018, she [[Celine Dion Live 2018|toured]] the Asia-Pacific region and grossed $56.5 million from 22 shows.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Wraps Summer Tour With $56 Million in the Bank|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8474119/celine-dion-summer-tour-56-million-grosses|author=Eric Frankenberg|work=Billboard|date=7 September 2018|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref> On 24 September 2018, she announced the end of her Las Vegas residency ''[[Celine (concert residency)|Celine]]'', with the final date set for 8 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=C\u00e9line Dion Announces End Of Her Las Vegas Residency After Eight Years|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8476550/celine-dion-announces-end-of-las-vegas-residency|author=Starr Bowenbank|work=Billboard|date=24 September 2018|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> She is currently working on a new English album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Is Back in the Studio Recording Something 'Great'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8476117/celine-dion-back-in-the-studio-photos|author=Josh Glicksman|work=Billboard|date=20 September 2018|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, she performed \"[[A Change Is Gonna Come]]\" at the \"Aretha! A Grammy Celebration for the Queen of Soul\" [[Aretha Franklin|Franklin]]'s tribute concert, to be broadcast in March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/all-star-lineup-pay-tribute-aretha-grammy-celebration-queen-soul|title=\"Aretha! A Grammy Celebration...\" Announced|author=Philip Merrill|website=grammy.com|date=27 December 2018|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-aretha-franklin-grammy-tribute-review-20190114-story.html|title=Review: Was Aretha Franklin properly honored at her all-star Grammy tribute?|author=Mikael Wood|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=14 January 2019|accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, she was one of 11 singers from Quebec, alongside [[Ginette Reno]], [[Diane Dufresne]], [[Isabelle Boulay]], [[Luce Dufault]], [[Louise Forestier]], [[Laurence Jalbert]], [[Catherine Major]], [[Ariane Moffatt]], [[Marie Denise Pelletier]] and [[Marie-\u00c9laine Thibert]], who participated in a [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] recording of [[Ren\u00e9e Claude]]'s 1971 single \"Tu trouveras la paix\" after Claude's diagnosis with [[Alzheimer's disease]] was announced.<ref>[https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1157795/tu-trouveras-la-paix-renee-claude-tete-palmares-itunes-canada \"La chanson pour Ren\u00e9e Claude en t\u00eate du palmar\u00e8s iTunes Canada\"]. [[Ici Radio-Canada]], 11 March 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2019, during a Facebook Live event, Dion announced her 2019/2020 [[Courage World Tour]], beginning in Quebec City on 18 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Announces 'Courage World Tour' and New Album|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8505582/celine-dion-announces-courage-world-tour-new-album|author1=Tallie Spencer|author2=Dave Brooks|work=Billboard|date=3 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref> She also announced a new English language album of [[Courage (Celine Dion album)|the same name]], to be released later in November 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion Plots First U.S. Tour in 10 Years|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/celine-dion-north-american-courage-world-tour-dates-817542/|author=Althea Legaspi|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September 2019, Dion released three songs, \"Lying Down\", \"Courage\", and \"Imperfections\" for her upcoming album, \"Courage\" as well as the pre-release of the album which will be available on 15 November 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2019/09/18/celine-dion-reveals-three-songs-new-album-courage/2353989001/|title=Celine Dion reveals three songs from new album 'Courage'|last=McDermott|first=Maeve|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| image1 = \n| width1 = 90\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Bee Gees 1992.JPG\n| width2 = 180\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Dion was able to collaborate with Barbra Streisand and the Bee Gees (above), both cited as great influences in her recording career.\n}}\n\n===Influences===\nDion cites idols as varied as [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Charles Aznavour]], [[Carole King]], [[Anne Murray]], [[Barbra Streisand]], and the [[Bee Gees]], all of whom she would eventually collaborate with.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4099|pure_url=yes}}|title=Celine Dion Bio |publisher=All Music Guide|year=2009|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2009/06/30/celine-dion-remembers-her-idol-michael-jackson|title=Celine Dion Remembers Her Idol, Michael Jackson|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=7 January 2010|date=30 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/singers-influenced-whitney-houston/story?id=15632234#6|title=From Beyonce to Gaga: 8 Singers Influenced by Whitney Houston|work=[[ABC News]]|publisher=ABC News Internet Ventures|date=16 February 2012|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> She has also expressed admiration for artists such as [[Mariah Carey]], [[Whitney Houston]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], citing the former two as having a profound influence on her own vocal style.<ref>{{Citation|title=FLASHBACK: 22-Year-Old Celine Dion Admires Madonna, Mariah and Whitney|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JAMLkz-F40E|language=en|access-date=26 October 2019}}</ref> Her music has been influenced by numerous genres, including pop, rock, [[gospel music|gospel]], [[R&B]], and [[soul music|soul]], and her lyrics focus on themes of poverty, world hunger, and spirituality, with an emphasis on love and romance.<ref name=\"autogenerated23\"/><ref>[http://www.pluggedinonline.com/music/music/a0001107.cfm Celine Dion, ''Let's Talk About Love''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829161008/http://www.pluggedinonline.com/music/music/a0001107.cfm |date=29 August 2008 }}, pluggedinonline.com; retrieved 13 September 2007.</ref> After the birth of her first child, her work increasingly focused on maternal love.<ref name=\"celebr\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2002/CelineDion-LetsTalkAboutLove.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715094203/http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2002/CelineDion-LetsTalkAboutLove.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 July 2011 |title=Celine Dion |work=plugged in.com|publisher=Focus on the Family|year=2009|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2003/CelineDion-OneHeart.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715094213/http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2003/CelineDion-OneHeart.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 July 2011 |title=Celine Dion-- One Heart |work=plugged in.com|publisher=Focus on the Family|year=2009|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2002/CelineDion-ANewDayHasCome.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715094219/http://www.pluggedin.com/music/albums/2002/CelineDion-ANewDayHasCome.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 July 2011 |title=A new Day Has Come|work=plugged in.com|publisher=Focus on the Family|year=2009|accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Musical style===\nDion has faced considerable criticism from critics, who state that her music often retreats behind pop and soul conventions, and is marked by excessive sentimentality.<ref name= Enc/><ref name=\"autogenerated24\"/> According to Keith Harris of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, \"[Dion's] sentimentality is bombastic and defiant rather than demure and retiring&nbsp;... [she] stands at the end of the chain of drastic devolution that goes Aretha\u2013Whitney\u2013Mariah. Far from being an aberration, Dion actually stands as a symbol of a certain kind of pop sensibility\u2014bigger is better, too much is never enough, and the riper the emotion the more true.\"<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Album Guide'' 2004.</ref> Her francophone releases, by contrast, tend to be deeper and more varied than her English releases, and consequently have achieved more credibility.<ref name=\"autogenerated21\"/><ref name=cbcc>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/celinedion.html|title=The real C\u00e9line: C\u00e9line Dion's new French album shows her personal side|publisher=CBC|year=2007|accessdate=7 January 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070531083109/http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/celinedion.html|archivedate=31 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCritics have stated that Dion's involvement in the production aspect of her music is fundamentally lacking, which results in her work being overproduced<ref name=\"cbcc\"/> and impersonal.<ref name=\"autogenerated21\"/> However, coming from a family in which all of her siblings were musicians, she dabbled in learning how to play instruments like piano and guitar, and practised with a [[Fender Stratocaster]] during the recording sessions of her album, ''Falling into You''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/02/23/arts/quebec-s-little-girl-conquering-the-globe.html|title=Quebec's Little Girl, Conquering the Globe|work=The New York Times|accessdate=7 January 2010|first=Anthony|last=Depalma|date=23 February 1997}}</ref>\n\nOccasionally, Dion has contributed to the writing of a handful of her English and French songs, as well as writing a few songs for other artists such as [[Marc Dupre]]. Additionally, as her career progressed, she found herself taking charge in the production of her albums. On her first English album, which she recorded before she had a firm command of the English language, she expressed disapproval, which could have been avoided if she had assumed more creative input.<ref name=\"autogenerated21\"/> By the time she released her second English album ''[[Celine Dion (album)|Celine Dion]]'', she had assumed more control of the production and recording process, hoping to dispel earlier criticisms. She stated, \"On the second album I said, 'Well, I have the choice to be afraid one more time and not be 100% happy, or not be afraid and be part of this album.' This is my album.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated21\" /> Besides her contributions to some of her early French albums, Dion wrote a few of the songs on ''[[Let's Talk About Love]]'' (1997) and ''[[These Are Special Times]]'' (1998).<ref name=\"evous.fr\">{{cite web|url = http://www.evous.fr/musique/Marc-Dupre-Entre-deux-mondes,11068.html|title = C\u00e9line Dion signe le single de Marc Dupr\u00e9 : Ecoutez 'Entre deux mondes'|publisher = Evous.fr|accessdate = 27 September 2014|date = 8 September 2011|language = French}}</ref>\n\nShe is often the subject of media ridicule<ref>See, e.g., [[Joel Selvin]], [http://www.sfgate.com/music/article/Celine-Dion-in-full-force-at-HP-Pavilion-3170389.php \"Celine Dion in full force at HP Pavilion\"], ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', 23 February 2009, E2. In this rather hostile review, Selvin wrote: \"You want cheese? She is a [[Velveeta]] volcano.\"</ref> and parody and is frequently impersonated on shows such as ''[[MADtv]]'', ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', ''[[South Park]]'', ''[[Royal Canadian Air Farce]]'', and ''[[This Hour Has 22 Minutes]]'' for her strong accent and on-stage gesticulations. However, she has stated that she is unaffected by the comments, and is flattered that people take the time to impersonate her.<ref name=\"vh1\" /> She even invited [[Ana Gasteyer]], who parodied her on ''SNL'', to appear on stage during one of her performances in New York. While she is rarely politically outspoken, in 2005 following the [[Hurricane Katrina]] disaster, Dion appeared on ''[[Larry King Live]]'' and tearfully criticized the [[George W. Bush|US government]]'s slow response in aiding the victims of the hurricane: \"There's people still there waiting to be rescued. To me that is not acceptable&nbsp;... How can it be so easy to send planes in another country to kill everybody in a second and destroy lives. We need to serve our country.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |work=C\u00e9line Dion takes swipe at Iraq war; donates $1&nbsp;m to Katrina victims |url=http://blogs.lasvegasmagazine.com/VegasLuxeLife/our-celine-dion-countdown%E2%80%94just-12-shows-to-go/ |accessdate=14 July 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071203005953/http://blogs.lasvegasmagazine.com/VegasLuxeLife/our-celine-dion-countdown%E2%80%94just-12-shows-to-go|archivedate=3 December 2007}}</ref> After her interview, she stated, \"When I do interviews with [[Larry King]] or the big TV shows like that, they put you on the spot, which is very difficult. I do have an opinion, but I'm a singer. I'm not a politician.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{cite book|last=Glatzer|first=Jenna|title=C\u00e9line Dion: For Keeps|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionforkee0000glat|url-access=registration|publisher=[[Andrews McMeel Publishing]]|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7407-5559-0}}</ref>\n\n===Voice and timbre===\nDion is often regarded as one of pop music's most influential voices.<ref name= Enc/><ref name=\"autogenerated21\"/><ref>Andersson, Eric. \"Who Inspired the Idols?\", ''Us Magazine'', 12 March 2007. p. 104</ref> According to Linda Lister in ''Divafication: The Deification of Modern Female Pop Stars'', she has been described as a reigning \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Queen of Pop]]\" for her influence over the record industry during the 1990s, alongside other female entertainers, including [[Whitney Houston]] and [[Mariah Carey]].<ref name= diva>\"If Ella Fitzgerald is the queen of jazz, Billie Holiday first lady of the blues, and Aretha Franklin the queen of soul, then who is the queen of pop? In the 1990s, it would seem to be a three-way tie between Whitney Houston, Mariah Carey, and Celine Dion. Certainly all three have their devotees and detractors, but their presence has been inescapable.\" in {{Cite news|last1=Lister|first1=Linda|title=Divafication: The Deification of Modern Female Pop Stars| newspaper=Popular Music and Society|volume=25|issue=3/4|page=1|year=2001|issn=0300-7766}}</ref> In a countdown of the \"22 Greatest Voices in Music\" by ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender Magazine]]'' and MTV, she placed ninth (sixth for a female), and she was also placed fourth in ''Cover Magazine''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s list of \"The 100 Outstanding Pop Vocalists\".<ref name=cove>{{cite web|title=Cover Magazine|work=The 100 Outstanding Pop Vocalists|url=http://covemagazine.com/100vocalists.html|accessdate=29 August 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716122547/http://www.covemagazine.com/100vocalists.html|archivedate=16 July 2006}}</ref><ref name=mtv22ist>{{cite web|title=MTV's 22 Greatest Voices in Music|work=covemagazine.com|url=http://www.listology.com/list/mtvs-22-greatest-voices-music|accessdate=15 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amiannoying.com/(S(ooqu0o45hssi4szgpvg5lb55))/collection.aspx?collection=534|title=22 Greatest Voices in Music|publisher=Amiannoying.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Dion is often compared to Mariah Carey and Whitney Houston for her vocal style and to her idol, [[Barbra Streisand]], for her voice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/02/23/arts/quebec-s-little-girl-conquering-the-globe.html|title=POP/JAZZ \u2013 Quebec's Little Girl, Conquering the Globe|location=Quebec Province (Canada)|work=The New York Times|date=23 February 1997|accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nShe possesses a three-octave range, from [[B (musical note)|B2]] to [[E (musical note)|E\u266d6]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bdwf8IuKTxI|title=Celine Dion \u2013 Live Vocal Range (B2 \u2013 Eb6) 3.2 Octaves|publisher=youtube.com|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jsC1WYJoLOI|title=Celine Dion's Live Vocal Range: B2-C#6 (3.4 Octaves)|publisher=youtube.com|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref> She once stated that she is a [[mezzo-soprano]].<ref name=\"Cyberpresse.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/arts/musique/200809/08/01-658078-celine-dion-chante-de-lopera-pour-kent-nagano.php |title=Alain de Repentigny : C\u00e9line Dion chante de l'op\u00e9ra pour Kent Nagano &#124; Musique |publisher=Cyberpresse.ca |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> However, attempts to adapt classical voice types to other forms of singing have been met with controversy.<ref>Peckham, Anne (2005). ''Vocal workouts for the contemporary singer.'' Boston: Berklee Press. pp. 117. {{ISBN|0-87639-047-5}}.</ref> Without making a classification, maestro [[Kent Nagano]] remarked, \"All you just sang was [[full lyric soprano]]\", after Dion auditioned with two solos from ''[[Carmen]]'', wanting to know if she could sing opera.<ref name=\"Cyberpresse.ca\"/> Her timbre has been described as \"thin, slightly nasal\"<ref name=\"NYTIS\">{{cite news|last=Holden |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/02/arts/review-pop-the-international-sound-of-celine-dion.html |title=Review/Pop \u2013 The International Sound of Celine Dion \u2013 Review |work=The New York Times |date=2 March 1994 |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> with a \"raspy\" lower register and \"bell glass-like high notes\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hazera |first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne |url=http://www.liberation.fr/culture/1999/06/21/dion-dans-les-grandes-largeurssamedi-et-dimanche-l-idole-canadienne-a-rempli-le-stade-de-france_275750 |title=Dion dans les grandes largeurs : Samedi et dimanche, l'idole canadienne a rempli le Stade de France |work=Lib\u00e9ration |date=21 June 1999 |accessdate=16 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe is often praised for her technical virtuosity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qFM1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=YyUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3124,21671065&dq=celine+dion+virtuosity|title=Celine Dion Takes Chances in Latest Album|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Jim Santella of ''[[The Buffalo News]]'' writes \"Like an iron fist in a velvet glove, the power of Celine Dion's voice is cloaked in a silky vibrato that betrays the intensity of her vocal commitment.\"<ref name=\"BuffaloT\">{{Cite news|last=Santella |first=Jim|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9C3898C21652&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D|title=The Diva Debate Queen Celine|work=The Buffalo News|date=19 September 1999|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> Jeff Miers, also of ''[[The Buffalo News]]'', says of Dion \"Her singing voice is absolutely extra-human. She hits notes in full voice, with a controlled vibrato and an incredible conception of pitch, like she's shucking an ear of corn\"<ref name=\"BuffaloT2\">{{Cite news|last=Miers|first=Jeff|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/entertainment/1544288/a_long_strange_trip_with_celine|title=A Long, Strange Trip with Celine|work=The Buffalo News|date=4 September 2008|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> Stephen Holden of ''[[The New York Times]]'' states that Dion has \"a good-sized arsenal of technical skills. She can deliver tricky melismas, produce expressive vocal catches and sustain long notes without the tiniest wavering of pitch. And as her duets&nbsp;... have shown, she is a reliable harmony voice.\"<ref name=\"NYTIS\"/> In an interview with ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'', Jean-Jacques Goldman notes that she has \"no problem of accuracy or [[tempo]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hazera|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|url=http://www.liberation.fr/culture/0101135681-celine-dion-en-vf|title=C\u00e9line Dion bio|work=Lib\u00e9ration|date=20 March 1995|accessdate=17 February 2011|language=fr}}</ref> According to [[Kent Nagano]], [[maestro]] of the [[Munich Symphony Orchestra]], she is \"a musician who has a good ear, a refinement, and a degree of perfection that is enviable\".<ref name=\"Cyberpresse.ca\"/> Charles Alexander of ''Time'' states, \"[Her] voice glides effortlessly from deep whispers to dead-on high notes, a sweet siren that combines force with grace.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated18\" />\n\nIn her French repertoire, Dion adorns her vocals with more nuances and expressiveness, with the emotional intensity being \"more tender and intimate\".<ref name=\"Denise Bombardier 2009, page 179\">Denise Bombardier, ''L'\u00e9nigmatique C\u00e9line Dion'', Albin Michel XO \u00e9ditions, 2009, page 179.</ref> Additionally, Luc Plamondon, a French singer-songwriter who has worked closely with Dion claims that there are three chanteuses (stylistically) that she uses: the Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois, the French, and the American.<ref name=\"Denise Bombardier 2009, page 179\"/> Her self-titled album was promoted with the slogan \"Remember the name because you'll never forget the voice.\"{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Legacy==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by Celine Dion}}\n[[File:Celine Dion both walk of fame stars.jpg|thumb|right|Dion's stars on [[Canada's Walk of Fame]] and the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]]]\nDion is regarded as one of pop music's most influential voices. [[Linda Lister]] describes her as a reigning ''Queen of Pop'' for her influence over the record industry during the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lister|first=Linda|title=Divafication: The Deification of Modern Female Pop Stars|url=http://lindalister.com/Divafication.pdf|work=[[Linda Lister]]|accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref> Her music and vocal style, alongside that of Mariah Carey and Whitney Houston, have been said to shape how the bulk of modern female pop vocalists sing. These three singers have been widely credited with reviving the [[power ballad]], and in doing so reshaping the adult contemporary radio format, making it one of the most popular formats of the 1990s and early 2000s. According to producer, musician, and former ''[[American Idol]]'' judge [[Randy Jackson]], Dion, Mariah Carey, and Whitney Houston are the voices of the modern era.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harp|first=Justin|title=''American Idol'' Randy Jackson: \"Whitney Houston was voice of generation\"|url=http://www.digitalspy.com.au/music/news/a367273/american-idol-randy-jackson-whitney-houston-was-voice-of-generation.html|accessdate=25 September 2013|newspaper=[[Digital Spy]]|date=23 February 2012}}</ref> Music critic and Dion biographer Carl Wilson notes that her \"fame and influence is also renewed and expressed regularly these days by American Idol, the largest mass musical phenomenon of the past decade, where Celine's stood solidly in its pantheon of singers for young people to emulate\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Hiebert|first=Paul|title=Why Celine Dion Will Always Be Popular \u2013 At Least While You're Alive|url=http://flavorwire.com/90128/why-celine-dion-will-always-be-popular-at-least-while-youre-alive|work=Flavorwire|accessdate=25 September 2013|date=12 May 2010}}</ref> Many contestants on the countless televised talent competitions that have risen at the turn of the millennium often emulate Dion, Houston and Carey and cite them as idols.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celine Still A Favourite Among American Idol Contestants|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/celine-still-favourite-among-american-idol-contestants|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615080941/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/celine-still-favourite-among-american-idol-contestants|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 June 2013|accessdate=25 September 2013|newspaper=The Official Celine Dion Site|date=20 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nMany artists have either mentioned Dion as a major influence or as one of their favourite singers including: [[Britney Spears]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6501914/billboard-cover-britney-spears-vegas-residency-new-album-boyfriend-sons|title=Billboard Cover: Britney Spears on Why Her Vegas Residency 'Clicked,' Being Inspired by Celine Dion and a New Album Not Being a 'Full Priority'|work=BIllboard|date=13 March 2015}}</ref> [[Rihanna]],<ref>{{cite web|title=ARTISTdirect's Exclusive Interview With Rihanna!|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/news/article/0,,3655378,00.html|work=ARTISTdirect|accessdate=25 September 2013|date=12 May 2006}}</ref> [[Christina Aguilera]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UoINJdqVsdw|title=Christina Aguilera talks about Celine Dion|publisher=YouTube|date=26 April 2013|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Frank Ocean]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Frank Ocean Gets Up Close in i-D Magazine|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/03/23/frank-ocean-gets-up-close-in-i-d-magazine|accessdate=9 February 2014|newspaper=[[Rap-Up.com]]|date=23 March 2012}}</ref> [[Adele]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Patterson|first=Sylvia|title=Mad about the girl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jan/27/popandrock.britawards2008|accessdate=9 February 2014|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|date=27 January 2008}}</ref> [[Josh Groban]],<ref name=\"grobanarchives.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grobanarchives.com/interviews/int070809b.html|title=Josh Groban Defends Celine Dion|publisher=Groban Archives|date=9 August 2007|accessdate=18 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409075232/http://www.grobanarchives.com/interviews/int070809b.html|archivedate=9 April 2014}}</ref> [[Delta Goodrem]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.perthnow.com.au/news/wa/delta-goodrem-teams-up-with-her-idol-celine-dion-ng-8ad32e6bbe66945a66c21d1328aef841|title=Delta teams up with idol Celine|date=12 October 2007|website=PerthNow|language=en|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> [[Jordin Sparks]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WDPnSQbtwBE |title=Jordin Sparks Shares Her Admiration For Mariah Carey, Celine Dion and Christina Aguilera|publisher=YouTube|date=3 September 2011|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Jake Zyrus]],{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} [[Leona Lewis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/lewis-to-meet-pop-idol-celine-dion_1048112|title=Lewis To Meet Pop Idol Celine Dion |publisher=Contactmusic.com|date=28 October 2007|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Jessie J]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JessieJ/status/13207197055|title=JessieJ: Celine Dion is a DON! #justsaying|publisher=[[Twitter.com]]|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[JoJo (singer)|Jojo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JoJoistheway/statuses/374770719441559552|title=JoJoistheway: I really have to learn French|publisher=Twitter.com|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Lea Michele]],<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=215685299794219008 |user=LeaMichele |title=Her show was sooooo good! And I got to meet and talk with her after the show. She is such an inspiring and amazing person! |date=20 June 2012 |url=https://twitter.com/LeaMichele/status/215685299794219008}}</ref> [[Jennifer Hudson]],<ref>[http://www.americanidol.com/contestants/season_3/jennifer_hudson] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629051009/http://www.americanidol.com/contestants/season_3/jennifer_hudson|date=29 June 2013}}</ref> [[Ariana Grande]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=llAd0xkYr74|title=Ariana Grande talking about celine dion|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Regine Velasquez]], [[Taylor Swift]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SQSjsbf8ufk|title=Celine Dion \u2013 At Seventeen (LIVE in HDTV) |publisher=YouTube|date=7 December 2008|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Vanessa Hudgens]],{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} [[The Canadian Tenors]], [[Faith Hill]], [[Katy Perry]], [[Sevyn Streeter]] and [[Kelly Clarkson]],<ref>[http://www.americanidol.com/contestants/season_1/kelly_clarkson] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003033802/http://www.americanidol.com/contestants/season_1/kelly_clarkson|date=3 October 2013}}</ref> among many others. Country singer [[Martina McBride]] is widely heralded by the press as the ''Celine Dion of Country music''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/11274241/1/martina-mcbride-target-exclusive-deluxe-edition-of-eleven-photo-business-wire.html|title=Martina McBride, Target Exclusive Deluxe Edition Of \"Eleven\" (Photo: Business Wire)|publisher=TheStreet|date=11 October 2011|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nNumerous artists have also praised Dion's voice, singing ability or expressed an interest in working with her including Met Opera conductor and musical director [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/806742/yannick-nezet-seguin-repetition-concert-musiciens|title=La fa\u00e7on Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin|last=Szacka|first=Alexandra|date=4 October 2016|website=ICI Radio Canada}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yannicknezetseguin.com/en/news/detail/yannick-nezet-seguins-way/|title=Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin's Way|last=Charland|first=Louise|date=4 October 2016|website=Yannicknezetseguin.com}}</ref> [[Beyonc\u00e9]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a482368/beyonce-got-parenting-tip-from-celine-dion-i-use-a-mommy-voice.html |title=Beyonc\u00e9 got parenting tip from Celine Dion: 'I use a mommy voice' \u2013 Showbiz News |publisher=Digital Spy|date=17 May 2013|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Carlos Santana]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/topics/entertainment/story.html?id=a300bad2-4877-481e-b591-7c0491922654|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314195854/http://www.canada.com/topics/entertainment/story.html?id=a300bad2-4877-481e-b591-7c0491922654 |url-status=dead|archive-date=14 March 2014|title=Legendary Santana lets his guitar fly solo|publisher=Canada.com|date=4 September 2008|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Elton John]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s0LYcewRn4E|title=Celine Dion & Elton John \u2013 H.E.A.R.T. Concert|publisher=YouTube|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[OneRepublic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/OneRepublic/posts/167060006639836|title=OneRepublic \u2013 Hey Everyone, tell us your secrets and we'll...|publisher=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Coldplay]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/cwcweyqlgbcw|title=Martin eyes Coldplay duet with Dion|publisher=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=10 October 2005|accessdate=18 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131122200538/http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/cwcweyqlgbcw/|archivedate=22 November 2013}}</ref> [[Sharon Osbourne]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MrsSOsbourne/status/399643105239891968|title=MrsSOsbourne: There is no better female artist|publisher=Twitter.com|date=10 November 2013|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Nicole Scherzinger]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NicoleScherzy/status/399659802487689216|title=NicoleScherzy: Such an honour to meet|publisher=Twitter.com|date=10 November 2013|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Ne-Yo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/1552164/ne-yo-teams-with-celine-dion-for-duet-it-definitely-made-me|title=Ne-Yo Teams With Celine Dion for Duet: 'It Definitely Made Me Question My Vocal Ability'|work=Billboard|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Carole King]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nAnYYNFH8p8|title=Celine Dion \u2013 The Reason (The Sessions)|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Barbra Streisand]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylywS5bP_Uw|title=YouTube|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Luciano Pavarotti]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2K7MoKJCoXw|title=Celine Dion \u2013 Making Album Let's Talk About Love|publisher=YouTube|date=7 December 2011|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Bee Gees]],<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2K7MoKJCoXw|title=Celine Dion \u2013 Making Album Let's Talk About Love|publisher=YouTube|date=7 December 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Sir George Martin]],<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> [[Justin Bieber]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nerienlouper.fr/44957-indiscretions-justin-bieber-en-duo-avec-celine-dion-pour-believe|title=Indiscr\u00e9tions: Justin Bieber en duo avec C\u00e9line Dion pour Believe?|publisher=Nerienlouper.fr|language=fr|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Jean-Jacques Goldman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d37XYawD-pc|title=C\u00e9line Dion et Jean-Jacques Goldman \"S'il suffisait d'aimer\" \u2013 Archive INA|language=fr|publisher=YouTube|date=9 July 2012|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Cher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-2gUi8wjMS0|title=Cher talks about Celine Dion's voice|publisher=YouTube|date=16 September 2011|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Timbaland]], \"Celine has such a beautiful, mesmerizing voice. She is so talented. I think we could create something that is a classic like she is already.\" Josh Groban remarked \"She's a powerhouse. In this day and age, when more and more studio-produced, tiny-tiny voices are being rewarded&nbsp;... she has this extraordinary instrument.\".<ref name=\"grobanarchives.com\"/> \"Celine is the best singer by far of her generation\" according to [[Diane Warren]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=APJrftBzSeA|title=Unfinished Songs New CelineDion & Diane Warren Song from the Film Unfinished Song|publisher=YouTube|date=28 June 2013|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> an opinion shared by [[Quincy Jones]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Jf16EedO-I|title=Celine Dion \u2013 MAKING OF I knew I loved you|publisher=YouTube|date=6 September 2010|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[Tommy Mottola]], and [[David Foster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G4IcQHFauDk|title=David Foster :Interview Mid 90s Pt2|publisher=YouTube|date=10 December 2006|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> Moreover, [[Shania Twain]] and [[Jennifer Lopez]] have praised her dynamic stage presence, with Jennifer Lopez commenting on American Idol: \"Celine gets on stage, she owns the stage, she runs all over that stage, she stops that stage.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V1G1bbBJS3M|title=J.Lo talking about celine dion on American idol 2011|publisher=YouTube|date=4 June 2011|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn a cultural level, Dion is credited for introducing francophone music to many non-francophone countries around the globe. Her albums ''[[D'eux]]'' and ''[[S'il suffisait d'aimer]]'' remain the best selling francophone albums in history, gaining unprecedented success in non-Francophone markets such as the United Kingdom, Poland, Netherlands, Portugal, Greece, Austria, Japan, and New Zealand. According to [[RFI Musique]], she \"has done her bit for French music over the years, assuring the success of French songs which would probably never have got beyond Francophone borders without her&nbsp;... Without Celine, French record sales would be dramatically lower!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rfimusique.com/musiqueen/articles/060/article_7167.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103025112/http://www.rfimusique.com/musiqueen/articles/060/article_7167.asp|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 January 2007|title=C\u00e9line Dion|publisher=RFI Musique|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> In 2008, she received the Legion of Honour from [[Nicolas Sarkozy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/node/77377 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224092105/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/node/77377|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 December 2013|title=Celine To Receive the French Legion of Honor Medal|publisher=Celinedion.com|date=18 May 2008|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> Sarkozy praised Dion and stated: \"France thanks you because your talent and success have contributed to the influence of the French language outside our borders\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liberation.fr/actualite/2008/05/22/celine-dion-decoree-de-la-legion-d-honneur-par-nicolas-sarkozy_15704|title=C\u00e9line Dion d\u00e9cor\u00e9e de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur par Nicolas Sarkozy|newspaper=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe is also credited for both revitalizing and revolutionizing the entertainment scene in Las Vegas with the gargantuan successes of her residencies there. She managed to re-popularize the Las Vegas \"residency\" as a desirable way for top artists to essentially tour in place, letting their fans come to them. Over the years, fellow established icons such as [[Elton John]], [[Bette Midler]], [[Rod Stewart]], [[Cher]], and [[Shania Twain]] followed suit.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110730195251/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/03/13/rich-vegas-poor-vegas.html Dead Link]</ref>{{better source|date=February 2015}} According to Gary Bongiovanni, president and editor-in-chief of [[Pollstar]] \"Celine redefined what artists can do in Las Vegas, helping to make it arguably the busiest entertainment city in the world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vegasmagazine.com/personalities/articles/celine-dion-the-queen-of-las-vegas |title=Celine Dion: The Queen of Las Vegas |publisher=Vegasmagazine.com |accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> By 2013, even the much-younger pop star [[Britney Spears]] had announced a Vegas residency, further cementing the extent of Dion's influence on the city as an entertainment capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/2013/09/16/britney-spears-las-vegas-contract-planet-hollywood-celine-dion|title=Britney Spears \u2013 Vegas Contract Is TITANIC ... But She Can't Touch Celine|publisher=TMZ.com |date=16 September 2013|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>{{better source|date=February 2015}} Kurt Melien, vice-president of entertainment at Caesar's Palace stated \"Celine was a pioneer without question&nbsp;... Twenty years ago, we couldn't have got someone the stature of Britney Spears to appear in Vegas. Stars likes her would never have considered it if Celine hadn't paved the way. She changed the face of modern Vegas.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/10477772/Why-is-Las-Vegas-gambling-15-million-on-Britney-Spears.html|title=Why is Las Vegas gambling $15 million on Britney Spears?|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\nRegarding her financial impact on Las Vegas, Stephen Brown, director of the Centre for Business and Economic Research in Las Vegas, commented \"People will come to the city just for her and they will spend money and as a consequence, she has an outsized impact on the economy\", then adding \"Bigger than Elvis, Sinatra and Liberace put together? Definitely.\" Estimations indicate that Dion's show will create up to 7,000 indirect jobs and around $114 million worth of new economic activity in each of the three years for which she has been contracted.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/8392760/Celine-Dion-promises-to-bring-the-sparkle-back-to-Las-Vegas.html|location=London, UK|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|first=Jacqui|last=Goddard|title=Celine Dion promises to bring the sparkle back to Las Vegas|date=19 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Canadian comedy music group, [[The Arrogant Worms]], released an album called ''[[Dirt (The Arrogant Worms album)|Dirt]]'' in 1999 which contained a song called \"Celine Dion\", about the singers [[Stalking|stalker]]-like affection for her.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael P. J. Kennedy|title=Going Top Shelf: An Anthology of Canadian Hockey Poetry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8NyKz81S_JMC&pg=PA91|year=2005|publisher=Heritage House Publishing Co|isbn=978-1-894384-99-5|page=91}}</ref> In 1999, Dion received a star on [[Canada's Walk of Fame]] and was inducted into the [[Canadian Broadcast Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/cab-announces-2009-broadcast-hall-of-fame-inductees/1000353791|title=CAB Announces 2009 Broadcast Hall Of Fame Inductees|accessdate=25 January 2009|date=25 April 1999|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526212705/http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/cab-announces-2009-broadcast-hall-of-fame-inductees/1000353791/|archive-date=26 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> She received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in January 2004, one which she dedicated to her father, who had died the month prior. In May 2003, she placed at No. 10 on [[VH1]]'s list of \"50 Greatest Women of the Video Era\",<ref>{{vcite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=66355#moreinfo |title=The Greatest \" Ep. 071 \"50 Greatest Women of the Video Era\"|publisher=[[VH1]]|date=17 May 2003|accessdate=17 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629061423/http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=66355|archivedate=29 June 2011}}</ref> She was ranked at No. 64 on their list of the \"200 Greatest Pop Culture Icons of All Time\".<ref>{{vcite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-200-greatest-pop-culture-icons-complete-ranked-list-70807437.html|title=The 200 Greatest Pop Culture Icons Complete Ranked List|publisher=VH1|date=21\u201325 July 2003|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> [[Falling into you]] is on [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]'s Definitive 200 list<ref name=\"The Definitive 200\">{{cite web|url=http://definitive200.com/200_list.php|title=The Definitive 200|publisher=[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=30 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070309200014/http://definitive200.com/200_list.php|archivedate=9 March 2007}}</ref>\n\n\"[[My Heart Will Go On]]\" was included in the list of ''[[Songs of the Century]]'', by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] and the [[National Endowment for the Arts]]. In 2007, Dion was ranked by ''[[Forbes]]'' as the 5th richest woman in entertainment with an estimated net worth of US$250&nbsp;million, though the ranking omitted non-working or retired celebrities.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 20 Richest Women In Entertainment|author=Lea Goldman and Kiri Blakeley|date=18 January 2007|url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/01/17/richest-women-entertainment-tech-media-cz_lg_richwomen07_0118womenstars_lander.html|work=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allwomenstalk.com/forbes-top-20-richest-women-in-entertainment|title=Forbes Top 20 Richest Women In Entertainment|accessdate=27 December 2011|work=All Women Stalk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6278145.stm|title=Oprah tops celebrity women list|date=19 January 2007|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> In August 2008, she received an honorary doctorate in music from the [[Universit\u00e9 Laval]] in Quebec City.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120215111312/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/arts/story.html?id=ad522fe1-e1d1-4c89-bb35-defeb06c04fe She's Dr. Dion now, courtesy of Laval U], Canada.com; retrieved 7 September 2008.</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Dion was named a [[FAO Goodwill Ambassador|Goodwill Ambassador]], a program created by the UN in 1999, sharing this accolade with Oscar-winner [[Susan Sarandon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2010/10/susan-sarandon-celine-dion-named-hunger-goodwill-ambassadors/1|title=Susan Sarandon, Celine Dion named hunger goodwill ambassadors|work=USATODAY.COM|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> She also received several [[state decoration]]s. In 2004, she was awarded [[Society of Singers|Society of Singers Lifetime Achievement Award]], and she was given France's highest award, the [[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'honneur]], by [[President of France|President]] [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] in May 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liberation.fr/actualite/2008/05/22/celine-dion-decoree-de-la-legion-d-honneur-par-nicolas-sarkozy_15704 |title=C\u00e9line Dion d\u00e9cor\u00e9e de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur par Nicolas Sarkozy |accessdate=5 June 2013 |publisher=Liberation.fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/story.html?id=10c4a258-589c-4aae-a907-7610b3323520|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013115046/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/story.html?id=10c4a258-589c-4aae-a907-7610b3323520|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 October 2013|title=Dion receives French Legion of Honour|publisher=Canada.com|accessdate=5 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July 2013, she was awarded the highest rank of the Order of Canada, the Companion of the [[Order of Canada]], by the [[Governor General of Canada]] and the investiture ceremony was held at [[Citadelle of Quebec]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Order Of Canada Investiture For Celine and Ren\u00e9|url=http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/order-canada-investiture-celine-and-ren%C3%A9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729030010/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/news/order-canada-investiture-celine-and-ren%C3%A9|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 July 2013|publisher=CelineDion.com|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> the same year she was inducted into the [[Gaming Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2013/9/5/celine-dion-to-be-inducted-into-the-gaming-hall-of-fame.html|title=Celine Dion to Be Inducted into the Gaming Hall of Fame \u2013 Music News \u2013 ABC News Radio|website=abcnewsradioonline.com|language=en|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n\n===Business endeavours===\nLes Productions Feeling Inc., also known as Feeling Inc. or just Feeling, is an artist management company based in Laval, Qu\u00e9bec, Canada, and owned by Dion and her husband and manager, Rene Ang\u00e9lil. She is also founder of Nickels Restaurant food chain. She and her husband also own Le Mirage Golf Club and [[Schwartz's|Schwartz's Restaurant]]. In association with Andre Agassi, Steffi Graf and Shaquille O'Neal, she opened a popular night club called ''Pure'', located at Caesars Palace.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=k1FsmOn30zcC&pg=PA70&lpg=PA70&dq=celine+dion+club+pure#v=onepage&q=celine%20dion%20club%20pure|title=Night+Day Las Vegas|last=Guides|first=Pulse|last2=Green|first2=Patrick|date=23 January 2017|publisher=ASDavis Media Group|isbn=9780975902288|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDion became an entrepreneur with the establishment of her [[franchising|franchise]] restaurant ''[[Nickels Grill & Bar|Nickels]]'' in 1990. She has since divested her interests in the chain and is no longer affiliated with ''Nickels'', as of 1997.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EpOtS5GprskC&pg=PA240&lpg=PA240&dq=celine+dion+nickels+1997#v=onepage&q=celine%20dion%20nickels%201997|title=Ren\u00e9 Angelil: The Making of C\u00e9line Dion: The Unauthorized Biography|last=Beaunoyer|first=Jean|date=1 March 2004|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=9781459714779|language=en}}</ref> In 2003, Dion signed a deal with [[Coty, Inc.]] to release ''[[Celine Dion Parfums]]''.<ref name=Davis>Davis, Mari (16 April 2003) \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20030608111214/http://www.fashionwindows.com/beauty/2003B/celine_dion02.asp Celine Dion Promotes Her Eponymous Perfume]\". Fashion Windows. Retrieved 12 August 2009</ref> Her latest fragrance, ''Signature'', was released in September 2011<ref name=\"celinedion1\"/> with an advertising campaign by New York agency Kraftworks NYC.<ref>[http://www.kraftworksnyc.com/main.php?page=clients&client_id=645212 Kraftworks NYC] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720064237/http://www.kraftworksnyc.com/main.php?page=clients&client_id=645212 |date=20 July 2013 }}</ref> Since its inception, ''Celine Dion Parfums'' has grossed over $850&nbsp;million in retail sales.<ref name=brilliance>[http://www.stylelist.com/2010/04/02/celine-dion-new-perfume-pure-brilliance/ Celine Dion to Launch New Perfume \u2013 Pure Brilliance] ''AOL Style List''. Retrieved 2 April 2010. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721113906/http://www.stylelist.com/2010/04/02/celine-dion-new-perfume-pure-brilliance|date=21 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwd.com/beauty-industry-news/fragrance/celine-dion-to-launch-pure-brilliance-fragrance-3020646|title=Celine Dion to Launch Pure Brilliance Fragrance|work=WWD|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> In October 2004, [[Air Canada]] hired Dion as part of their promotional campaign to unveil new service products and an updated [[livery]]. \"[[You and I (Celine Dion song)|You and I]]\", the theme song sung by Dion, was written by advertising executives working for Air Canada.<ref>Alberts, Sheldon. \"A Canadian liftoff; Dion 'flattered' her Air Canada ad chosen as Clinton's campaign song\". ''[[National Post]]''. 20 June 2007. pg A3.</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nDion has actively supported many charity organizations, worldwide. She has promoted the [[Canadian Cystic Fibrosis Foundation]] (CCFF) since 1982, and became the foundation's National Celebrity Patron in 1993.<ref>McLellan, Stephanie Simpson. \"Celebrating the Mother\u2013Child Bond\". ''Today's Parent'', p. 32. 1 May 2004.</ref> She has an emotional attachment to the foundation; her niece Karine succumbed to the disease at the age of sixteen, in Dion's arms. In 2003, she joined a number of other celebrities, athletes, and politicians, including [[Josh Groban]] and [[Yolanda Adams]] to support \"World Children's Day\", a global fundraising effort sponsored by [[McDonald's]]. The effort raised money from more than 100 nations and benefited orphanages and children's health organizations. In addition, she has been a major supporter of the [[Tony Martell|T.&nbsp;J. Martell Foundation]], the [[Diana Princess of Wales]] Memorial Fund, and many health and educational campaigns. During the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina, she donated $1&nbsp;million to the victims of the storm, and held a fund-raising event for the victims of the [[2004 Asian tsunami]], which subsequently raised more than $1&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/music/news/article_3487.php/Celine_Dion_to_Raise_One_Million_for_Tsunami_Victims |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514161413/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/music/news/article_3487.php/Celine_Dion_to_Raise_One_Million_for_Tsunami_Victims|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 May 2008|title=Celine Dion to Raise One Million for Tsunami Victims|last=Wray|first=James|date=12 January 2005|publisher=Monsters & Critics|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> After the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake]], she donated $100,000 to China Children & Teenagers' Fund and sent a letter showing her consolation and support.<ref>Celine Dion [http://blog.sina.com.cn/s/blog_4776146401009wp5.html Her letter to China Children & Teenagers' Fund], sina.com.cn; retrieved 15 October 2009.</ref> Since 2004, she is involved, alongside husband Ren\u00e9 Angelil, with the Qu\u00e9bec gay community by supporting the publication of health and HIV prevention materials in ''Gay Globe Magazine'', owned by journalist Roger-Luc Chayer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gayglobe.us/blog/?p=5065|title=C\u00e9line contre le SIDA|publisher=Gayglobe.us|date=9 December 2011|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> She is also a member of Canadian charity Artists Against Racism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artistsagainstracism.org/artists/|title=Artists \u2013 Artists Against Racism|language=en-US|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> In November 2018, she launched a gender-neutral clothing line for kids, ''Celinununu''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/celine-dion-gender-neutral-clothing-line_us_5bec5639e4b057089767bfd5|title=C\u00e9line Dion Launches a Gender-Neutral Clothing Line for Kids|last=Wong|first=Curtis M.|date=14 November 2018|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:C\u00e9line Dion Ren\u00e9 Angelil 2012.jpg|thumb|Dion and husband [[Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil]] in 2012]]\nAs the youngest of 14 children, Dion grew up wearing hand-me-downs and sharing a bed with several sisters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/09/best-dressed-list-2019|title=Vanity Fair 2019 Best Dressed List|last=Bullock|first=Maggie|date=5 September 2019|website=Vanity Fair|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> As a baby, she slept in a drawer to save on a crib.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2012/01/celine-dion-201201|title=Caesars Princess|last=Heilpern|first=John|date=14 December 2011|website=Vanity Fair|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> She was bullied at school and called \"Vampire\", owing to her teeth and skinny frame.<ref name=\":4\" /> Local tabloids even dubbed her \"Canine Dion\" in the teenage years of her career.<ref name=\":3\" /> She often spoke of running home from school to play music in the basement with her brothers and sisters. \"I detested school\", she would later write in her autobiography. \"I had always lived surrounded by adults and children a lot older than me. I learned everything I needed to know from them. As far as I was concerned, real life existed around them.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> Dion's eldest sister was already in her 20s, married, and pregnant with her first child at the time Dion's mother, [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Dion|Th\u00e9r\u00e8se]], was pregnant with Celine.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Dion : La Vie Est un Beau Voyage|last=Germain|first=Georges-H\u00e9bert|publisher=Libre Expression|year=2006|isbn=2764802978|location=Montreal|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/theresedionlavie0000germ}}</ref>\n\nDion first met her husband and manager, [[Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil]], in 1980, when she was 12 and he was 38, after her brother, Michel Dondalinger Dion, sent him a demonstration recording of ''\"[[Ce n'\u00e9tait qu'un r\u00eave]]\"'' (\"It Was Only a Dream/Nothing But A Dream\"), a song she, her mother the former Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Tanguay, and her brother Jacques Dion had jointly written and composed. Over subsequent years, Ang\u00e9lil guided her to stardom in francophone territories.\n\nAfter the dissolution of Ang\u00e9lil's second marriage, he and Dion took a professional break and he had spent the major part of the year in Las Vegas, while Dion was learning English and taking dance and singing lessons in Montreal. Upon his return, \"he avoided being alone with me for too long a time\",<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/196 196]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/196}}</ref> she said in her 2000 autobiography, [https://www.amazon.com/Celine-Dion-My-Story-Dream/dp/0380819058 ''My Story, My Dream'']. Meanwhile, she kept a photo of Ang\u00e9lil under her pillow, writing, \"Before I fell asleep, I slipped it under the pillow, out of fear that my mother, who always shared a room with me, would find it.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/134 134]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/134}}</ref> \"Less and less could I hide from myself the fact that I was in love with Rene; I had all the symptoms.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/152 152]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/152}}</ref> \"I was in love with a man I couldn't love, who didn't want me to love him, who didn't want to love me.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/169 169]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/169}}</ref> Dion's mother, who traveled everywhere with the singer until she was 19, was initially wary of her daughter's growing infatuation with a much older and twice-divorced Ang\u00e9lil but Dion was insistent, telling her mother \"I'm not a minor. This is a free country. No one has the right to prevent me from loving whoever I want to.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollns / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/159 159]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/159}}</ref>\n\nTheir professional relationship eventually turned romantic after Dion's win at the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] in Dublin in 1988; she was 20.<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/2000 2000]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/2000}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Rene Angelil Le Maitre Du Jeu|last=Germain|first=Georges-Herbert|publisher=Libre Expression|year=2009|isbn=9782764804186|location=Montreal|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reneangelillemai0000germ/page/293 293]|url=https://archive.org/details/reneangelillemai0000germ/page/293}}</ref> The romance was only known to family and friends for five years, though Dion nearly revealed all in a tearful 1992 interview with journalist [[Lise Payette]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/266 266]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/266}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvanouvelles.ca/2018/09/06/celine-dion-rend-un-vibrant-hommage-a-lise-payette-1|title=C\u00e9line Dion rend un vibrant hommage \u00e0 Lise Payette|last=Murphy|first=Caroline G.|date=6 September 2018|website=TVA Nouvelles|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sPlt4mqASTI|title=Celine Dion \u2013 T\u00eate-\u00e0-t\u00eate Interview|date=1992|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> Many years later, Payette penned the song \"Je cherche l'ombre\" for Dion's 2007 album, [[D'elles|D'Elles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b4qTtyiFsY4&t=13m09s|title=C\u00e9line Dion \u2013 D'elles TV Special \u2013 TVA|date=21 May 2007|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nDion and Ang\u00e9lil became engaged in 1993, on Dion's 25th birthday,<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/268 268]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/268}}</ref> and made their relationship public in the liner notes of her 1993 album, [[The Colour of My Love]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/279 279]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/279}}</ref> They married on 17 December 1994, at [[Notre-Dame Basilica (Montreal)|Notre-Dame Basilica]] in Montreal, Quebec. On 5 January 2000, Dion and Ang\u00e9lil renewed their wedding vows in Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celine Dion : 2000, C\u00e9line Dion & Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil's remarriage (USA)|url=http://www.celinedion.us/event,rene-angelil-remarriage,20000105r.html|website=CelineDion.US|accessdate=15 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205164957/http://www.celinedion.us/event,rene-angelil-remarriage,20000105r.html|archive-date=5 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2000, Dion had two small operations at a fertility clinic in New York to improve her chances of conceiving, after deciding to use [[in-vitro fertilization]] because of years of failed attempts to conceive. Their first son, Ren\u00e9-Charles Ang\u00e9lil, was born on 25 January 2001. In May 2010, Ang\u00e9lil announced that Dion was 14 weeks pregnant with twins after a sixth treatment of in-vitro fertilization. On Saturday, 23 October 2010, at 11:11 and 11:12&nbsp;am respectively, at [[St. Mary Medical Center (Long Beach)|St. Mary's Medical Center]] in [[West Palm Beach, Florida]], Dion, by [[Caesarean section]], gave birth to healthy fraternal twins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedion.com/news/celine-gives-birth-twins |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317033158/http://www.celinedion.com/news/celine-gives-birth-twins |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 March 2011 |title=Celine Gives Birth to Twins!! |work=Celinedion.com |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2010}}</ref> The twins were named Eddy, after Dion's favourite French songwriter, [[Eddy Marnay]], who had also produced her first five albums, and Nelson, after former South African President [[Nelson Mandela]].<ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-31749_162-20021142-10391698.html Celine Dion's Twins Named Nelson and Eddy]; retrieved 28 October 2010. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030185436/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-31749_162-20021142-10391698.html|date=30 October 2010 }}</ref> She appeared with her newborn sons on the cover of 9 December 2010 issue of the Canadian edition of ''[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.ca/magazine/cover-hello-canada-199.html|title=HELLO! \u2013 The place for daily celebrity news|publisher=hellomagazine.ca|accessdate=28 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212222310/http://www.hellomagazine.ca/magazine/cover-hello-canada-199.html|archivedate=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2016, Ang\u00e9lil died from throat cancer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celine Dion loses husband Rene Angelil to cancer|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/celebrity/celine-dion-loses-husband-rene-anglil-to-cancer-20160114-gm6cl3.html|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=15 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"WCVBTV\">{{cite news|title=Singer Celine Dion's brother has cancer \u2013 Her husband died Thursday|url=http://www.wcvb.com/news/singer-celine-dions-brother-has-cancer/37461884?Content%20Type=Story|accessdate=16 January 2016|work=[[WCVB-TV]]|date=15 January 2016|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> His funeral was held on 22 January 2016, in [[Notre-Dame Basilica (Montreal)|Notre-Dame Basilica]] in Montreal, where he and Dion wed 21 years earlier. The couple's eldest son, Ren\u00e9-Charles, gave the eulogy just three days before his 15th birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/rene-angelil-funeral-memorable-moments-1.3416300|title=Ren\u00e9 Ang\u00e9lil funeral: Memorable moments|date=22 January 2016|website=CBC News|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> Following Ang\u00e9lil's passing, Dion became the sole owner and president of her management and production companies, including CDA Productions and Les Productions Feeling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ic.gc.ca/app/scr/cc/CorporationsCanada/fdrlCrpDtls.html?corpId=3976564&V_TOKEN=1567473463907&crpNm=feeling%20productions&crpNmbr=&bsNmbr=|title=Government of Canada, Federal Corporation Information|date=30 June 2018|website=Government of Canada|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nvsos.gov/sosentitysearch/CorpDetails.aspx?lx8nvq=pmMjwx1oal9Lgsa83iGChg%253d%253d&nt7=0|title=Nevada Secretary of State, Online Entity Search|date=12 March 2019|website=Nevada Secretary of State|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo days after Ang\u00e9lil's death \u2013 on what would have been her husband's birthday \u2013 Dion's brother, Daniel, died at age 59, also of cancer.<ref>{{cite news|title=C\u00e9line Dion's brother Daniel, 59, has died|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/celine-dion-brother-daniel-dead-1.3407188|work=[[CBC News]]|date=16 January 2016|accessdate=24 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2018, Dion's management team announced that she had been dealing with hearing irregularities for the past 12\u201318 months due to [[Patulous Eustachian tube]] and would undergo a [[minimally invasive procedures|minimally invasive surgical procedure]] to correct the problem after ear-drop medications appeared to be no longer working.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/21/entertainment/celine-dion-cancels-concerts/index.html|title=Celine Dion cancels Vegas shows due to ear issues|author-first=Sandra|author-last=Gonzalez|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=19 April 2018|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOwing to her slight frame, Dion has for decades been subject of eating disorder rumors, which she has consistently denied:<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ellecanada.com/culture/celebrity/celine-dion-is-our-summer-2019-cover-star/|title=C\u00e9line Dion Is Our Summer 2019 Cover Star|last=Craft|first=Vanessa|date=11 June 2019|website=Elle Magazine|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/style/celine-dion-new-face-of-loreal-at-51-body-shamers/|title=C\u00e9line Dion Is the New Face of L'Or\u00e9al at 51 \u2013 and She's Shutting Down Body-Shamers|last=Rubenstein|first=Janine|date=2 April 2019|website=People|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> \"I don\u2019t have an eating problem, and there\u2019s nothing more I can say about it\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-family-matters-vol-51-no-8/|title=Family Matters|last=Helligar|first=Jeremy|date=1999|website=People|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> \"My work requires me to be in great physical shape. I wouldn't have been able to live up to a hundred shows a year and travel ceaselessly from one end of the world to the other if I had eaten too much or not enough, or if, as certain magazines have claimed, I made myself throw up after each meal.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=My Story, My Dream|last=Dion|first=Celine|publisher=HarperCollins / Avon|year=2000|isbn=0380819058|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/320 320]|url=https://archive.org/details/celinedionmystor00dion/page/320}}</ref> She has often spoken about having been bullied at school and lacking confidence in her early years in the business:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/04/51-year-old-cline-dion-is-the-new-face-of-loral-paris.html|title=51-Year-Old C\u00e9line Dion Is the New Face of L'Or\u00e9al Paris|last=Hou|first=Kathleen|date=2 April 2019|website=New York Magazine / The Cut|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> \"I didn\u2019t have, visually, what it took. I was not pretty, I had teeth problems, and I was very skinny. I didn\u2019t fit the mold\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/celine-dion|title=Celine Dion on Wearing That Suit Backwards at the Oscars, and Why She's Sick of Singing \"My Heart Will Go On\"|last=D\u2019Souza|first=Nandini|date=1 October 2007|website=W Magazine|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, Dion took up ballet under the guidance of her former dancer, Naomi Stikeman, who also previously performed for [[The National Ballet of Canada]] and [[La La La Human Steps]], and former Cirque du Soleil dancer-turned-fashion-illustrator, Pepe Mu\u00f1oz, who is also part of her styling team.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.naomistikeman.com/|title=www.naomistikeman.com|last=Stikeman|first=Naomi}}</ref> She is also a skier and a regular at her son Ren\u00e9-Charles' hockey games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/Music/2017/01/13/Celine-Dion-posts-photo-of-first-Christmas-without-Rene-Angelil/3921484325469/|title=UPI: Celine Dion posts photo of first Christmas without Rene Angelil|last=Martin|first=Annie|date=13 January 2017|website=United Press International|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2017/08/celine-dion-is-a-super-fun-hockey-mom|title=C\u00e9line Dion just proved she's the most fun hockey mom|last=Jhaveri|first=Hemal|date=15 August 2017|website=USA Today|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larevue.qc.ca/rene-charles-angelil-sur-la-glace-de-larena-de-lachenaie/|title=Ren\u00e9-Charles Ang\u00e9lil sur la glace de l'ar\u00e9na de Lachenaie|last=Talbot|first=V\u00e9ronick|date=30 August 2016|website=Journal Revue|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Celine Dion albums discography|Celine Dion singles discography|List of songs recorded by Celine Dion|l3 = songs}}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''French-language studio albums'''\n*''[[La voix du bon Dieu]]'' (1981)\n*''[[C\u00e9line Dion chante No\u00ebl]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Tellement j'ai d'amour...]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Les chemins de ma maison]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Chants et contes de No\u00ebl]]'' (1983)\n*''[[M\u00e9lanie (album)|M\u00e9lanie]]'' (1984)\n*''[[C'est pour toi]]'' (1985)\n*''[[Incognito (Celine Dion album)|Incognito]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Dion chante Plamondon]]'' (1991)\n*''[[D'eux]]'' (1995)\n*''[[S'il suffisait d'aimer]]'' (1998)\n*''[[1 fille & 4 types]]'' (2003)\n*''[[D'elles]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Sans attendre]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Encore un soir (album)|Encore un soir]]'' (2016)\n{{col-2}}\n'''English-language studio albums'''\n*''[[Unison (Celine Dion album)|Unison]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Celine Dion (album)|Celine Dion]]'' (1992)\n*''[[The Colour of My Love]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Falling into You]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Let's Talk About Love]]'' (1997)\n*''[[These Are Special Times]]'' (1998)\n*''[[A New Day Has Come]]'' (2002)\n*''[[One Heart]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Miracle (Celine Dion album)|Miracle]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Taking Chances]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Loved Me Back to Life]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Courage (Celine Dion album)|Courage]]'' (2019)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Concert tours and residencies==\n{{Main|List of Celine Dion concerts|}}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Tours'''\n*Les chemins de ma maison (1983\u20131984)\n*[[C\u00e9line Dion en concert (tour)|C\u00e9line Dion en concert]] (1985)\n*[[Incognito tourn\u00e9e|Tourn\u00e9e Incognito]] (1988)\n*[[Unison Tour]] (1990\u20131991)\n*[[Celine Dion in Concert]] (1992\u20131993)\n*[[The Colour of My Love Tour]] (1994\u20131995)\n*[[D'eux Tour]] (1995\u20131996)\n*[[Falling into You: Around the World]] (1996\u20131997)\n*[[Let's Talk About Love World Tour]] (1998\u20131999)\n*[[Taking Chances World Tour]] (2008\u20132009)\n*[[Tourn\u00e9e Europ\u00e9enne 2013]]\n*[[Summer Tour 2016]]\n*[[Celine Dion Live 2017]]\n*[[Celine Dion Live 2018]]\n*[[Courage World Tour]] (2019\u20132020)\n{{col-2}}\n'''Residencies'''\n*[[A New Day...]] (2003\u20132007)\n*[[Celine (concert residency)|Celine]] (2011\u20132019)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Celine Dion videography}}\n\n* ''[[Touched by an Angel]]''\n* ''[[The Nanny]]''\n* ''[[All My Children]]''\n* ''La fureur de C\u00e9line''\n* ''Des fleurs sur la neige''\n* ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'' as Juliana (singing voice)\n* ''[[C\u00e9line sur les Plaines]]''\n* ''[[Celine: Through the Eyes of the World]]''\n* ''[[Sur la piste du Marsupilami]]''\n* ''[[Hell's Kitchen (U.S. TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]]''\n* ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]]''\n\n==See also==\n*{{Books-inline|Celine Dion}}\n* [[List of best-selling music artists]]\n* [[List of highest-grossing concert tours]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist\n| 30em\n| refs =\n<ref name=\"gazette.gc.ca\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/1998/1998-05-16/pdf/g1-13220.pdf\n |title=Canada Gazette Part I, Vol. 132, No. 20\n |last=LeBlanc\n |first=The Right Honourable Rom\u00e9o\n |date=16 May 1998\n |work=gazette.gc.ca\n |publisher=[[Governor General of Canada]]. [[Canada Gazette]]. [[Rideau Hall|Government House]]\n |location=[[Ottawa]]\n |page=6 (page 1096 in the [[Canada Gazette]])\n |trans-title=|format=PDF ??? -->\n |accessdate=20 March 2011\n |authorlink=Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310221828/http://gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/1998/1998-05-16/pdf/g1-13220.pdf\n |archivedate=10 March 2012\n\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gg.ca\">\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=3837&t=12&ln=Dion\n| title       = C\u00e9line Dion, C.C., O.Q\n| author      = The Right Honourable Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc\n| year        = 1998\n| work        = gg.ca\n| publisher   = [[Governor General of Canada]]\n| location    = [[Ottawa]]\n| trans-title = | accessdate = 20 March 2011\n| authorlink  = Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ordre-national.gouv.qc.ca\">\n{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.ordre-national.gouv.qc.ca/membres/membre-en.asp?id=86\n| title      = Home > Members > C\u00e9line Dion: Officer (1998)\n| 